{ Welcome, dear chess players, to the second database in our series, "Spanish for White." The Spanish Opening, also known as the Ruy Lopez, stands as one of the most captivating and deeply studied openings in chess theory. For over 150 years, it has been a cornerstone for the worldâ€™s top players, offering rich strategic depth and flexibility. In this database, weâ€™ll focus on all the systems where Black plays with Bc5. As always, youâ€™ll have access to a 15-minute video overview and 20 exercises to test your knowledge and sharpen your skills. In Chapter 1, we will start by discussing all the move orders and the ideas behind each system. } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 ( 3... Nf6 4. O-O Bc5 { Bc5 in the Berlin move order will be discussed in Chapter 2. } ) ( 3... Bc5 { This move is called "Cordel variation" and we will investigate it in Chapter 3. } ) 4. Ba4 Nf6 ( 4... Bc5 5. c3 { [%cal Gg8e7,Rg8f6] In Chapter 4 we will discuss why 4...Nf6 is not good here, and we will analyze the modern system where Black plays 4...Nge7. } ) 5. O-O b5 ( 5... Bc5 6. c3 b5 { Against this move order, we will take the chance to move our bishop directly to c2 } ( 6... O-O { In Chapter 5 we will discuss this interesting continuation. } 7. d4 { Black's plan is to play } 7... Ba7 $5 { And it has been recently tried by a lot of top players. } ) 7. Bc2 d5 { This is a very concrete variation and the one where you will need to work more. We will examine it very extensively from Chapter 7 to Chapter 11. } ( 7... d6 { is not so good because our bishop is already on c2. We will discuss it in Chapter 6. } ) ) 6. Bb3 Bc5 { The main Arkhangelsk is a very serious and concrete variation. In chapter 15, GM Baadur Jobava will show you a fresh direction where you don't need to memorize too many variations, and you have very good chances of achieving a slightly better and more pleasant position. } ( 6... Bb7 7. d3 { [%csl Rb7,Gd3] d3 is a very good move for White when Black's bishop goes to b7. } 7... Bc5 ( 7... Be7 { will be analyzed in Chapter 12. } ) 8. a4 O-O { This is Black's main continuation, and we will analyze it in Chapter 14. } ( 8... d6 { will be analyzed in Chapter 13, together with 8...b4. } ) ) *

