{ Welcome, dear chess players! In this first chapter, we will discuss Black's and White's ideas behind each move order. It's extremely important to carefully study this chapter before diving deeper into the theory of each variation. } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 ( 3... Nf6 4. O-O Bc5 { Bc5 in the Berlin move order is not so strong because of } 5. Nxe5 $1 { and we will analyze it in Chapter 2. } ) ( 3... Bc5 $5 { This is the so-called "Cordel Variation", which was also recommended by Pavel Eljanov in Modernchess. } 4. c3 ( 4. O-O { allows } 4... Nd4 { and it's difficult for White to find an advantage. } ) 4... Nf6 5. d4 { [%csl Gb5,Gc4] } 5... exd4 6. e5 { [%csl Gb5] it's like a Max Lange of the Italian variation, with the only difference being that White's bishop is on b5 and not on c4. } 6... Nd5 7. O-O { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gc3d4,Gc5b4,Gd4c3,Gd1d5] and now Black needs to play very accurately. } ( 7. cxd4 { allows } 7... Bb4+ ) 7... Be7 $1 ( { the standard } 7... O-O $2 { is bad because of } 8. cxd4 Be7 9. Qb3 Nb6 10. d5 $16 ) 8. cxd4 d6 { [%csl Gd6] This is the main position of the Cordel variation that we will analyze in Chapter 3. Let me point out that in the same position with a6-Ba4 included, White's position would be much better because of } 9. Qb3 { which is not so strong here because Black can play } 9... Be6 $1 ) 4. Ba4 Nf6 ( 4... Bc5 { [%cal Gg8e7] } 5. c3 Nge7 $5 { Is an extra option for Black. } ( 5... Nf6 $6 { Black shouldn't play in the style of the 3...Bc5 Cordel variation, because after } 6. d4 exd4 7. e5 Nd5 8. O-O Be7 9. cxd4 d6 { [%csl Ga4,Ga6] } 10. Qb3 $1 { [%csl Ga4,Ga6] The inclusion of the moves a6-Ba4 makes it impossible for Black to continue with Be6, because the b7 pawn will be hanging. You can appreciate how a small detail like the inclusion of a6-Ba4 can seriously influence the evaluation of a position! } ) 6. O-O Ng6 7. d4 { [%csl Ge5,Gg6][%cal Gg6e5] } 7... Ba7 { We will analyse this position in Chapter 4. } ) 5. O-O b5 ( 5... Bc5 $5 { [%csl Ga4] This is a tricky move order. Black's idea is to play the main Arkhangelsk variation 5...b5 6.Bb3 Bc5, but having already excluded all the Nxe5 options. } 6. c3 b5 ( 6... O-O $5 7. d4 Ba7 { Is an interesting sideline, and we will analyze it in Chapter 5. } ) 7. Bc2 { [%csl Gc2] We have to play this move if we want to avoid the big mainline of the Arkhangelsk. } ( { If we play } 7. Bb3 { then after } 7... d6 8. a4 Rb8 { Black has excluded our Nxe5 variation, and he forced us to enter in the big mainline. } ) 7... d5 $1 { This is Black's extra option against 7.Bc2. This is also the most challenging part of this database. In order to avoid the mainstream theory in the main Arkhangelsk, we need to carefully study this very concrete continuation. In my opinion, it's very interesting to play this variation from the White's side, but we really need to study a lot because the positions are very concrete. We will discuss this variation from chapter 7 to chapter 11. } ( { if Black plays } 7... d6 { then after } 8. d4 Bb6 9. a4 { [%csl Rb3,Gc2][%cal Gc8b7,Gc8g4,Ga8b8] We are playing the Arkhangelsk mainline, but with the big difference that our bishop is on c2 and not on b3, which is a huge improvement for us. We will discuss it in Chapter 6. } ) ) 6. Bb3 Bc5 ( 6... Bb7 7. d3 { [%csl Rb7,Gd3,Ge4] d3 is a good move when Black's bishop is on b7. } 7... Bc5 ( 7... Be7 { is a possible continuation. } 8. Nc3 O-O 9. a3 Nd4 $5 { An independent option that we will check in Chapter 12. } ( 9... d6 { transposes to Spanish for White part 1, Chapter 2. } ) ) 8. a4 { [%cal Gd7d6,Gb5b4,Ge8g8] Now, Black can continue with b4, d6 and 00. We will analyze all options in Chapters 13 and 14. } ) 7. a4 Rb8 ( 7... Bb7 8. d3 { transposes in 6...Bb7. } ) 8. Nxe5 $5 { This is our recommendation to avoid the mainstream theory. } ( 8. c3 { This is White's mainstream continuation. This variation has thousands of games, and it's extremely difficult for White to find ideas. } 8... d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5 { White's most interesting direction. } ( 10. axb5 { is White's old mainline, but Black is fine everywhere, in my opinion. } ) 10... Ba7 11. h3 O-O ( 11... Bb7 $5 { Is another very serious move. } ) 12. Be3 { here Black can try many moves like Ra8, Re8 or exd4. } ) 8... Nxe5 9. d4 Bxd4 10. Qxd4 d6 11. Bf4 $5 { Only 50 games have been played in this position, and we can achieve a very interesting game. We will analyze this in Chapter 15. } *

