1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { Black can also play Bc5 in the Berlin move order } 3... Nf6 4. O-O Bc5 $6 { but it's considered dubious because of } 5. Nxe5 $1 { Black can now choose between Nxe4 and Nxe5. } 5... Nxe4 ( 5... Nxe5 6. d4 { Black doesn't have a proper reaction because, after Bxd4, White is just better developed and has the pair of bishops, while after Bd6, White can play dxe5-Bxe5, and f4! is decisive. For this reason, Black should first attack our bishop (with a6 or c6) and only then decide how to react. } 6... c6 ( 6... a6 7. Be2 $1 { The right retreat. } ( 7. Ba4 $6 { Is a mistake because of } 7... b5 $1 8. Bb3 Bxd4 9. Qxd4 d6 $13 { [%cal Gc7c5,Gc5c4] Black threats c7-c5. } ) 7... Nxe4 ( 7... Bxd4 8. Qxd4 d6 9. c4 $16 { White has a big advantage because of the better structure and the pair of bishops. } ) 8. dxc5 $1 Nxc5 { Now, we get a lot of tempi against Black's knights: } 9. b4 $1 Ne6 10. f4 $1 { [%cal Gf4f5] } 10... Nc6 11. f5 Ned4 12. f6 $18 { Black is busted. } ) 7. dxe5 $1 ( 7. Be2 $6 { Is not great anymore because Black can play } 7... Bd6 8. dxe5 Bxe5 9. f4 { and Black has now } 9... Bc7 $13 { With a playable position. } ) 7... Nxe4 ( 7... cxb5 $2 { Would lead to a positional disaster for Black: } 8. exf6 Qxf6 9. Nc3 $16 { [%cal Gc3d5] Nd5 next, with a big advantage. } ) 8. Bd3 d5 9. exd6 Nf6 ( 9... Nxd6 $4 { Loses on the spot: } 10. Re1+ Be6 11. Rxe6+ fxe6 12. Qh5+ $18 { [%cal Gh5e8,Gh5c5] } ) 10. Re1+ Be6 { From a first look, the position looks normal for Black; if he manages to play 00 and take on d6, he will be fine, but he is not in time. } 11. Nc3 Qxd6 ( 11... O-O 12. Bf4 $16 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Yd3h7] Black can no longer take on d6. } ) ( 11... Bxd6 12. Bf5 $16 ) 12. Bg5 $1 { Black misses one important tempo to have a good position. } 12... O-O-O { Black's best continuation, but it is very sad: } ( 12... O-O 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Ne4 $18 { White is winning. } ) ( 12... Bd4 13. Bh4 $1 { [%cal Gh4g3] We prepare Bg3. } 13... O-O-O 14. Bg3 Qc5 15. Qf3 $16 { [%cal Gf3f4] Qf4 next, and Black faces serious problems. } ) 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Ne4 Qd4 15. Nxc5 Qxc5 16. Qf3 $16 { [%csl Rf6,Rf7] We enjoy a better structure for free. } ) 6. Qe2 ( 6. Nf3 $5 { [%cal Gd2d4,Gd4d5] Also deserves attention. We plan d4-d5. } ) 6... Nxe5 7. d4 $1 { A strong intermezzo. } ( { in the case of } 7. Qxe4 { after } 7... Qe7 $11 { Black's position is fine. } ) 7... Be7 ( 7... Bxd4 $4 8. Qxe4 $18 { [%csl Rd4,Re5] Black loses a piece. } ) ( 7... Qe7 8. dxc5 Ng6 $1 { Black's best continuation, but White gets a risk-free better endgame. } ( 8... Nxc5 { is Black's most popular continuation, but White gets a big advantage: } 9. Nc3 Ng6 ( 9... c6 10. f4 $1 Ng6 11. f5 Ne5 12. b4 $18 ) 10. Be3 Ne6 11. f4 { [%cal Gf4f5] f5 is a big threat. } 11... f5 12. g4 $1 O-O 13. gxf5 Rxf5 14. Bd3 $16 { [%cal Ge2g4,Ga1e1] } ) 9. Nc3 ( 9. b4 $5 { Also deserves attention. } ) 9... Nxc3 10. Qxe7+ Nxe7 11. bxc3 b6 12. Rd1 { [%csl Rc8] } 12... bxc5 13. Ba3 $14 { [%csl Ga3,Gb5][%cal Ya3c5] Bxc5 next. We are much more active, and our pair of bishops is very strong. } ) 8. dxe5 a6 $14 { This is Black's best defense, but it has never been played in practice. } ( 8... Nc5 { Is Black's standard and natural continuation, but after } 9. Bc4 O-O 10. Nc3 d6 11. Rd1 $16 { [%cal Gc1f4,Ge5d6] We have a big advantage in development, and we can just continue with Bf4 and exd6 at some point. } ) 9. Bd3 Nc5 10. Bc4 ( 10. Rd1 $5 { Is another interesting direction, for example: } 10... Nxd3 11. Rxd3 O-O 12. Nc3 d6 13. Qh5 $14 { [%cal Gc1f4,Gc3d5] White has two bishops, but we are much more active. The engine evaluates +0,30. } ) 10... d5 $1 ( 10... O-O 11. Rd1 $1 { [%cal Gb1c3,Gc1f4] Nc3-Bf4 next, and it is similar to the 8...Nc5 line. } ) 11. exd6 Qxd6 12. Nc3 Be6 $1 ( 12... O-O $4 { Would be a huge mistake because of } 13. Rd1 $18 { And Black loses material. } ) 13. Rd1 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Qc6 $1 ( 14... Qe6 $2 15. Nd5 $16 { [%cal Gc1e3,Gd5c7] } ) 15. Nd5 Bd6 $1 { As you can see, Black needs to find a lot of only moves. } 16. Bg5 Ne6 $1 ( 16... O-O $4 { Is again losing: } 17. Ne7+ Bxe7 18. Bxe7 $18 { [%csl Rc5,Rf8][%cal Ge7f8,Ge7c5] } ) 17. Qe4 h6 $1 { As you can see, Black not only needs to know 8...a6! but he also needs to play many accurate moves, which is not easy at all over the board. } ( 17... O-O $6 { once again, it is bad: } 18. Be7 $1 Rfe8 19. Bxd6 cxd6 20. c4 $16 { White has a big positional advantage. } ) 18. Bh4 O-O 19. Ne7+ ( { Black's idea is that after } 19. Be7 { now } 19... Ng5 $11 { Is a strong resource, and that's why he had to include 17...h6! } ) 19... Bxe7 20. Qxc6 bxc6 21. Bxe7 Rfb8 22. Ba3 $14 { [%csl Rc6,Rc7] Black got a slightly worse but holdable endgame. If your opponent finds 8...a6!, which is a novelty, and then plays 15 best moves, you will have to accept playing a slightly better endgame... In the second game you face this variation, you may choose 10.Rd1!? } *

