1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 { This variation has become very popular recently. } 4. c3 ( { if you choose this move order, then you need to deal with } 4. O-O Nd4 $5 { Which is a solid option for Black, and it's difficult for White to find an advantage. } ) 4... Nf6 { The alternatives are not great for Black. } ( 4... Qf6 $2 { Is a bad move } 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 Qg6 { [%csl Rg6] The queen on g6 is just misplaced. } 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 Nge7 9. O-O d5 ( { if Black plays } 9... O-O { then } 10. d5 $18 { is decisive. } ) 10. Ne2 $18 { [%cal Ge2f4] Nf4 next, and White has a huge advantage. } ) ( 4... d6 $4 { Would be a huge mistake because of } 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Kf1 $1 { [%cal Gd4d5,Gd1a4] } 7... Bd7 8. Qa4 $18 { Black loses material. } ) ( 4... f5 $6 { It's a dubious gambit. } 5. d4 $1 fxe4 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nxe5 Bd6 8. Qh5+ g6 9. Qe2 Bf5 { Anand-L'Ami, 2017. } 10. Bf4 $5 Nf6 11. Nd2 Qe7 12. O-O O-O-O 13. Ndc4 $16 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf2f3,Ya1e1] We have a stable, strong knight on e5. We can continue with Rae1-f3, and White has a good positional advantage. } ) 5. d4 ( 5. O-O O-O 6. d4 Bb6 7. a4 $5 { is a positional alternative: } 7... a6 $1 { Black's most precise continuation. } 8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. Nxe5 Nxe4 10. Re1 Nd6 11. a5 Ba7 12. Bf4 Be6 13. Nd3 $14 { [%cal Rc6c5,Gb1d2,Gd1f3] We stop c7-c5, and we can continue with Nd2-Qf3. White's advantage is not big, but we can play a long game, in which it will be difficult for Black to fully equalize. } ) 5... exd4 6. e5 Nd5 { Compared to the Max Lange, Black can now play Nd5 because our bishop is on b5 and not on c4. } ( 6... Ne4 $6 7. O-O d5 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. h3 $14 { [%csl Gb5] We are playing a Max Lange variation with an extra tempo because our bishop is already on b5. } ) 7. O-O ( 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. O-O d6 $13 { I have tried to find an advantage here, but it's not easy because Black is very solid. } ) 7... Be7 $1 { Black's most precise continuation and it has been played by many strong players like Abdusattorov, Indijc, Eljanov... } ( 7... O-O $2 { Is a known mistake because White can now play } 8. cxd4 Be7 9. Qb3 $1 Nb6 10. d5 $16 { And Black is worse. } ) 8. a4 $5 { This is my recommendation. It has been played only in three games, but by strong players like Santos, Motylev. } ( 8. cxd4 d6 { I have tried to analyse this position, but it seems to me that Black is doing fine: } 9. exd6 Qxd6 $5 { easier than 9...exd6, in my opinion. } 10. Re1 a6 $1 11. Ba4 Be6 12. Nc3 O-O $13 { Black has a solid position and a balanced game. } ) 8... a6 ( 8... d6 $14 { It is the engine's recommendation, but not an easy one! } 9. Nxd4 Qd7 $1 { It is a very precise move. The idea is that after exd6, Black can recapture with the queen. } ( 9... Bd7 $6 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Re1+ Nde7 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Bg5 $14 { [%csl Rc6,Rc7] White can enjoy a pleasant game because of the better pawn structure. } ) 10. exd6 Qxd6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd3 O-O 13. Qc2 h6 14. Nd2 $14 { Engine's evaluation is only +0,20, but in a practical game, White has a pleasant positional advantage because of the better pawn structure. } ) ( 8... a5 9. Nxd4 O-O 10. Nf3 $14 { This is my novelty. First of all, we force Nb6. } ( 10. Nf5 { was played in the game Santos-Iturrizaga, 2023, but after } 10... d6 11. Nxe7+ Ncxe7 $11 { Black is doing fine. } ) ( 10. Nc2 $14 { Deserves attention. } ) 10... Nb6 11. Bf4 { Black cannot play the liberatory d7-d6 on his terms. } 11... d6 ( 11... f6 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Re1 d6 14. h3 $14 { [%cal Rc8g4,Gb1d2,Gd2e4] We prevent Bg4, and we can continue with Nd2-Ne4. } ) 12. exd6 Bxd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Qxd6 cxd6 15. Nbd2 $14 { White has a good endgame because of the better pawn structure. } ) 9. Bc4 Nb6 10. Bb3 d5 ( 10... O-O $4 11. a5 $18 { Black loses on the spot. } ) 11. exd6 $1 ( 11. cxd4 $6 Bg4 $13 { Black is doing great. } ) 11... Qxd6 12. a5 Nd5 13. Nxd4 { Black misses a tempo to be completely fine. } 13... O-O { was played in the game Motylev-Koellner, 2023. } ( 13... Nxd4 { It's critical, but it doesn't equalize: } 14. Qxd4 Nf6 15. Qxd6 Bxd6 16. Re1+ $14 { Black doesn't have a comfortable continuation. } ) ( 13... Bd7 $14 { Black plans to retake on c6 with the bishop in the case of Nxc6, but we have a concrete strong continuation: } 14. Nd2 Nxd4 15. Ne4 $3 { A very strong idea found by a strong engine. } 15... Qe5 16. cxd4 Qxe4 17. Re1 { We will regain the piece. } 17... Qg4 $1 ( 17... Qf5 18. Re5 $16 { White is better. } ) 18. Qxg4 Bxg4 19. Bxd5 $14 { [%csl Rb7,Rf7][%cal Gd5b7,Gd5f7] Black must decide if to sacrifice the b7 pawn or the f7 one. } ) 14. Nxc6 $1 { We force Black to recapture with the pawn. } 14... bxc6 15. Bc2 $14 { [%cal Gb1d2,Gd2e4] Thanks to the better pawn structure, White has an advantage and won in a nice style in Motylev-Koellner, 2023. CONCLUSIONS: The Cordel 3...Bc5 variation recently regained popularity, but I think that my recommendation 8.a4!? puts serious questions. } *

