1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Bc5 5. c3 Nge7 $5 { When Black starts with 4...Bc5, his idea is usually to develop the knight on e7. This set-up became fashionable for Black only in the last few years. } ( 5... Nf6 $6 { Compared to the Cordel variation that we have analyzed in the previous chapter, here, White has a much-improved version because of the inclusion of the moves a6-Ba4. } 6. d4 exd4 ( 6... Ba7 $6 { rare line, but better to know the refutation. } 7. Nxe5 $1 { Most of players choose 7.00, but 7.Nxe5 is a direct refutation. } 7... Nxe5 8. dxe5 Nxe4 9. Qg4 $1 { Only move to get the advantage. } 9... Bxf2+ 10. Ke2 Qh4 11. Qxg7 Rf8 12. b4 $14 { [%csl Yc5][%cal Gc1h6,Rf2c5,Yb4c5] Again, this is White's only way to fight for the advantage. If not for this move, we would be worse. Now, we treat Bh6, and Black will no longer have Bc5. } ( 12. Bh6 $2 Bc5 $19 { Black is winning. } ) 12... f6 $1 { This is Black's best continuation. We can stop here, or check a long sequence of only moves shown by the engine: } ( 12... Qh5+ 13. g4 Qg6 14. Qxg6 fxg6 15. Bh6 Rf7 16. Kd3 $18 { [%csl Re4] Black lost his knight in a funny way! } ) 13. e6 $1 { Don't be surprised, every move will have an exclamation mark because both sides have to often find only moves. } 13... Qh5+ $1 { [%cal Gh5d5] } 14. g4 Qd5 15. Bb3 { It looks like White's strongest continuation. } ( 15. Bh6 $5 { Is another possibility. } 15... Qc4+ $1 16. Kd1 Qd3+ 17. Kc1 Be3+ 18. Kb2 Bxh6 19. Qxh6 Qe2+ 20. Bc2 dxe6 21. Qxh7 Nf2 22. Nd2 $1 Nxh1 23. Rxh1 Bd7 $3 24. Bg6+ Kd8 25. Qh6 $1 Rg8 26. Bf7 $36 { We could continue this line forever! The engine shows +0,30, and it needs to be investigated. } ) 15... Qb5+ $1 { Black has to force first c4. } ( 15... Qe5 $4 { Is a mistake immediately because the bishop on b3 will be very strong. } 16. Bh6 $18 ) 16. c4 Qe5 17. Bh6 Ng5+ 18. Kxf2 Qd4+ { Now, we have different ways to reach the c2 square, but the final position will be the same: } 19. Ke2 Qe4+ ( 19... Nxe6 $2 20. Qxh7 Qxa1 21. Bxf8 Kxf8 22. Rf1 $18 ) 20. Kd2 Qf4+ 21. Kc2 Qe4+ 22. Kb2 { at this point Black has to take on e6. } 22... Nxe6 23. Re1 $3 { Again, only move for us. } 23... Qxe1 24. Qxh7 Qe2+ 25. Bc2 Nd4 26. Nd2 $1 Nxc2 27. Kxc2 Rf7 28. Qg6 { [%cal Ga1f1,Gf1f6] } 28... d6 $1 29. Rf1 Ke7 30. Rf4 Be6 31. Re4 Qxh2 32. Bf4 Qh7 { And White's advantage relais in the fact that now } 33. Qf5 $1 { is possible, and after } 33... Qxf5 34. gxf5 $16 { Black gets a very dangerous endgame. I am sorry for the long variation, but we entered in a line where both sides had to play a lot of only moves to get this final position. This variation is still unknown in the chess theory! } ) 7. e5 Nd5 8. O-O Be7 9. cxd4 d6 { In this same position, Black is fine without the inclusion of a6-Ba4, but here } 10. Qb3 $18 { [%cal Rc8e6] Is refuting the line. The key difference is that Black doesn't have Be6 because of Qxb7. } ) 6. O-O Ng6 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gg6e5] Black defends the e5 pawn, and in the case of d4, he is ready to retreat the bishop on a7 without the need to exchange on d4. } 7. d4 Ba7 { This is the starting position of this new variation. } 8. Bxc6 $5 { This is my recommendation. We accept Black's pawn sacrifice, and our opponent will need to proof the compensation. } ( 8. Bg5 { Is White's most common continuation. The idea is to provoke f6 and only then play Be3. } 8... f6 9. Be3 O-O 10. Nbd2 d6 11. Re1 Kh8 $5 { White is definitely slightly better, but Black achieves a complicated position where all the three results are possible. } ) 8... dxc6 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qe7 { This is Black's most common and natural move. } ( 10... Qxd1 $6 11. Rxd1 { Difficult to believe that Black has full compensation in the endgame. For example: } 11... Bg4 12. Rd3 O-O { Shuvalova-Tari, 2022. } 13. Kf1 $1 Rad8 14. Rxd8 Rxd8 15. Bd2 $16 { [%cal Gf2f3,Gf1e1] We will continue with f3-Ke1 and then slowly develop our pieces, and Black has no way to recover the missing pawn. } ) ( 10... O-O { Black allows us to force an endgame. } 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Nd2 $14 { [%cal Gf1e1,Gd2f1,Gc1e3] We will continue with Re1-Nf1-Be3. } ) ( 10... Qh4 { Black wants to play aggressively, but our position is very solid, and we have little to fear. } 11. Qf3 { [%cal Gf3e4,Yc1e3] The queen on f3 not only defends the pawn on e4, but also prepares the Be3 positional exchange. } 11... Rg8 $5 { [%cal Gc8g4,Yf3f4,Yg7g5] Black's idea is Bg4-Qf4-g5. } ( 11... g5 $2 { is premature because of } 12. Qf6 $1 Rg8 13. Nd2 $18 { [%cal Gd2f3] Nf3 next, and White has a big advantage. } ) ( 11... Bg4 12. Qf4 Qh5 { We can now play our original idea: } 13. Be3 $14 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Qxe5 15. Nd2 $14 { [%cal Gf2f4] In this structure, our knight is superior to Black's bishop. In addition, Black faces immediate small problems. } 15... Bd7 { Black's idea is to retreat the bishop before White is able to play f4-f5, as shown in the 15...00 variation. } ( 15... O-O-O $2 { would be a mistake because of } 16. h3 Be6 17. Qa7 $18 ) ( 15... O-O $6 { allows } 16. f4 Qe7 17. f5 $16 { [%csl Rg4] And Black needs to deal with the bishop on g4. } ) 16. f4 Qe7 17. e5 f5 $1 { This is Black's best continuation, but after } ( 17... O-O 18. f5 $16 { [%csl Ge5,Gf5] White has a huge advantage. } ) 18. Nf3 $14 { It is clear that White has a pleasant positional edge. } ) 12. Nd2 Bg4 ( 12... g5 $2 13. Qf6 $18 { [%cal Gd2f3] trans in 11...g5. } ) 13. Qd3 $1 { A very deep move. We prevent 000, and after Black plays the natural } ( 13. Qf4 g5 $13 { And Black is doing great. } ) ( 13. Qg3 $6 { doesn't offer much because after } 13... Qxg3 14. hxg3 { Black can play } 14... O-O-O $11 ) 13... Rd8 { only now we will play } 14. Qg3 $1 { because after } 14... Qxg3 15. hxg3 $14 { [%csl Re8][%cal Gf1e1,Gd2f1,Gc1e3,Rg8e8,Re8e5] White's king is still on e8, which means that Black will lose time if he wants to play Re8-Rxe5. Our idea will be to continue with Re1-Nf1-Be3. } ) 11. Qf3 $1 { We give back our extra pawn with the idea to play for piece activity: } 11... Qxe5 12. Bf4 Qe7 13. Qg3 { [%csl Rc7,Rg7][%cal Gg3g7,Gf4c7] We threaten both the c7 and g7 pawns. } 13... Be6 { This is Black's most concrete continuation, and it was played in the recent game MVL-Nakamura, 2024. } ( 13... O-O { Ideally, Black would like to castle long, but the immediate short castle allows him to play without sacrificing material. } 14. Nd2 ( 14. Bxc7 $6 Qxe4 $11 ) 14... Bb6 $1 { [%csl Rc7] We have different possible plans, but I like the following one: } 15. Rae1 Be6 16. e5 { [%cal Gf4g5] we prepare Bg5 or Ne4. } 16... Bf5 { [%cal Ye7e6] this is Black's most logical move, because it is intended against Ne4, and it also frees the e6 square for Black's queen. } 17. Bh6 $14 { My recommendation. First, we provoke Bg6 } 17... Bg6 { and only now we go for the bishops exchange: } 18. Be3 Bxe3 19. Qxe3 $14 { [%csl Rg6][%cal Gf2f4,Yf4f5,Rf5e6] Black's bishop is worse on g6 than on f5, at least for two reasons: - Black will not be able to eventually play Be6; - When we play f4, f5 will be a serious threat. } ) ( 13... f6 14. Bxc7 h5 { Black can try to play without Be6, but after } ( 14... Be6 15. Nd2 { trans in 13...Be6. } ) 15. Nd2 h4 16. Qg6+ { he should be ready to play with the king on f8. } 16... Kf8 17. Bf4 Be6 18. e5 $1 fxe5 19. Rae1 { [%csl Rf8] Black's king is very vulnerable, that's why Black needs to play precisely. } 19... Qf6 20. Qe4 Qxf4 21. Qxf4+ exf4 22. Rxe6 Re8 23. Rxe8+ Kxe8 24. Nf3 $14 { [%csl Ya7,Gf3][%cal Gh2h3,Gf1e1,Ge1e4] We have a very pleasant endgame. We can fix the kingside pawns by playing h3, or we can use the Re1+-Re4 idea. } ) 14. Bxc7 f6 { [%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] Black plans h5-h4. } 15. Nd2 h5 16. Nf3 { [%cal Rh5h4] } 16... g5 { Black insists on the h4 idea. } 17. h4 $14 { This novelty is White's critical continuation. } ( 17. Nd4 { Was played in the MVL-Nakamura game, but after } 17... h4 $1 18. Qd6 Qxd6 19. Bxd6 Kf7 $13 { Black's position was very fine. } ) 17... gxh4 18. Nxh4 Rh7 $3 { This is Black's strongest continuation. } ( 18... Rg8 $6 { Black's most natural move, but it's a mistake! } 19. Qh2 Rg7 20. Bd6 Qd7 { [%cal Ge8c8] Black is ready for 000, but we have the very strong } 21. c4 $3 { [%cal Gc4c5] our idea is to play c5 ad to make irrelevant Black's bishop on a7. } 21... O-O-O ( 21... Bxc4 $2 { is even a worse idea, because after } 22. Nf5 $18 { White gets a winning position. } ) 22. c5 $16 { [%csl Ra7] } ) 19. Bf4 Rg7 $1 ( 19... O-O-O $2 20. Rad1 Rg8 21. Nf5 $1 { It's an important move that allows us to get a winning position. } 21... Qf8 22. Qf3 $18 ) 20. Qf3 Bg4 21. Qd3 Qd7 $1 ( 21... Rd8 $2 22. Qc2 $16 { [%csl Re8][%cal Ge4e5,Ya1e1] e5 next, and Black is much worse. } ) 22. Qxd7+ Rxd7 23. Rae1 $14 { [%cal Ge4e5] We can continue with e5. The engine evaluates +0,35, which means that with precise play, Black should hold the endgame, but as you know, in a practical game, it's never easy to defend such endgames! CONCLUSIONS: After 8.Bxc6!? Black doesn't have the typical three-results game he wishes when playing the Bc5 c3 Nge7!? variation. Instead, he must be very well-prepared not to end up in a pawn-down position without compensation. } *

