1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5 6. c3 { Black now has two main continuations: 00 and b5. In this chapter, we will analyze 6...00. } 6... O-O { This move is not obvious as after } 7. d4 Ba7 $1 { is Black's idea. } ( 7... exd4 $2 { would be a huge mistake because } 8. cxd4 Ba7 9. e5 Nd5 10. Nc3 $18 { White has a winning advantage. } ) ( 7... Bb6 $6 { [%cal Rb7b5] Is less precise than Ba7 because Black will no longer have b5 ideas: } 8. Re1 $1 d6 9. h3 $1 { [%csl Rb6,Gd4,Ge4][%cal Rc8g4,Rb7b5] We prevent Bg4 ideas, and we can enjoy a strong center. If Black's bishop was on a7, Black would have here b5! But in this situation, his position is just worse. } 9... Bd7 { Black can get a solid, but worse position: } ( 9... h6 10. Be3 $1 Nxe4 { Critical move, but White gets an advantage in the following concrete variation: } 11. d5 Bxe3 12. Rxe3 Nxf2 13. Kxf2 Ne7 { in the game Lohia-Nagy, 2024, White played 14.c4, but } 14. Qd2 $14 { is a strong improvement. } 14... c5 15. dxc6 Nf5 16. Re4 Qb6+ 17. Ke1 bxc6 18. Qf2 Qc7 19. c4 $16 { [%cal Gb1c3] Nc3 next, and Black doesn't have enough compensation for the missing piece. } ) 10. Bc2 Re8 $14 { Black's only good continuation; otherwise, we are just typically much better. } 11. Be3 { [%cal Gb1d2] We play normal moves Be3-Nbd2, and Black has to do something before we are able to consolidate. } 11... exd4 $1 ( { if Black plays a slow move like } 11... h6 $2 { after } 12. Nbd2 $16 { we have a typically better Ruy Lopez position. } ) 12. cxd4 Nb4 $1 ( 12... Nxe4 $4 { Doesn't work because of } 13. d5 $18 { And Black loses material. } ) 13. Nc3 Nxc2 14. Qxc2 $14 { [%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ge4e5] Black has two bishops, but all our pieces are well-placed, and we have a strong center. Right now, we are ready for e5. } ) 8. Bg5 $1 { This is definitely White's critical continuation. } ( 8. dxe5 { is natural, but after } 8... Nxe4 $13 { White has tried some ideas, but it seems that Black has enough counterplay. } ) ( 8. Re1 { This was strong against 7...Bb6, but now the difference is that after } 8... d6 9. h3 { Black has } 9... b5 $1 10. Bc2 Bb7 $13 { [%csl Re4][%cal Gb7e4] Where his bishop on b7 is very strong, as it puts pressure against our e4 pawn. } ) 8... h6 ( 8... exd4 { was recently played in the game Muzychuk-Vaishali, 2024. White has a lot of interesting ideas, but I offer to follow that game: } 9. e5 h6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 { Visually, Black's structure looks terrible, but Black hopes to get a counterplay concretely. } 11. Qd2 Kg7 ( 11... d6 { Was played in the game Svane-Buckels, 2023. White missed the strong } 12. Qxh6 $14 { Which is immediately winning. } 12... Nxe5 13. cxd4 $18 ) 12. cxd4 fxe5 13. dxe5 d6 { [%csl Ra1,Rb1] our only problem is that our queenside pieces are not developed yet, that's why Black's position is still holdable. } 14. Bxc6 $1 { Our only chance to fight for something. } 14... bxc6 15. Rd1 Bg4 16. Qc3 $1 { [%csl Gc3,Rg7][%cal Ge5d6,Gc3g7] We create a lot of threats, but the engine has found } 16... Bxf3 $1 17. exd6+ Qf6 18. gxf3 Rfd8 $1 19. d7 Rab8 $1 20. b3 Rb5 $1 { And with a lot of moves, Black survives. Still, I think that this endgame is quite unpleasant for Black from the practical point of view: } 21. Qxf6+ Kxf6 22. Nc3 Re5 { This position was reached in the recent game Muzychuk-Vaishali, 2024. Now, I want to offer a small improvement. } 23. Kf1 $14 Ke7 24. Re1 Rxe1+ 25. Rxe1+ Kxd7 26. Re4 $14 { We can play a long and two-results endgame, in which Black should play very well to make a draw. } ) 9. Bh4 exd4 ( 9... b5 $2 10. dxe5 g5 11. exf6 gxh4 { White wins in brilliant style: } 12. e5 $3 bxa4 13. Qd2 { [%cal Gd2h6] } 13... Kh7 14. Qd3+ Kh8 15. Ng5 $3 hxg5 16. Qf3 $18 { And Black can resign. } ) ( 9... g5 $2 { is also bad because of the typical sacrifice } 10. Nxg5 Nxe4 ( 10... hxg5 11. Bxg5 $18 { [%cal Gf2f4] f4 next, and White is winning. } ) 11. Nf3 $1 Ng5 12. Nxg5 hxg5 13. f4 $1 { The key move. After } 13... gxh4 14. Qg4+ Kh8 15. Qh5+ Kg7 16. fxe5 $18 { Black's position is lost. } ) ( 9... d6 { It's less popular than 9...exd4, but objectively, it might be Black's best continuation. } 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. dxe5 { This is a very safe move, and Black gets an unpleasant position without any winning chances: } ( 11. Nbd2 $5 { is a good alternative if you want to play an interesting, slightly better game. } 11... Re8 12. Re1 $14 { Alekseenko-Nihal, 2021. } ) 11... dxe5 12. Nxe5 Qe7 13. Bg3 $5 { Practically the simplest, in my opinion. } ( 13. Nxc6 $6 Qxe4 $1 14. Nxa7 Bh3 $3 15. gxh3 Rfd8 $36 { Thanks to an amazing preparation, Black took the initiative in MVL-Van Foreest, 2021. } ) ( 13. Nf3 $5 { Is another possible direction: } 13... Qxe4 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nbd2 Qf4 16. Re1 $14 { [%cal Gd2b3,Gb3d4] Nb3-Nbd4 next. Yes, Black has two bishops, but his structure is awful. You can check the game Dragnev-Kaczur, 2021. } ) 13... Nxe4 14. Nxc6 Qc5 15. Nxa7 Qxa7 16. Qc1 $14 { [%cal Gb1d2] Nd2 next. Maybe Black can hold, but it's very unpleasant. } ) 10. Re1 $1 ( { to better understand the 10.Re1 move, let's check what happens after } 10. e5 { now, Black is forced to play } 10... g5 { and our problem is that after } 11. Nxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 { Black has } 12... Nxe5 $13 { That's why the move 10.Re1 is so important! } ) 10... b5 { Was played twice by the Indian GM Pranesh, but it's objectively not equalizing: } ( 10... dxc3 $2 11. Nxc3 $16 { [%cal Gc3d5] White gets another piece into the game, and Black's position is very precarious. } ) ( 10... d6 { Black's most common continuation. } 11. Bxc6 $1 { Only critical move. } ( 11. cxd4 Bg4 $13 ) 11... bxc6 ( 11... dxc3 12. Nxc3 bxc6 { White can now choose between Qc1 and h3. In both cases, we have a preferable position. } 13. h3 $14 ( 13. Qc1 $36 { [%cal Ge4e5] } ) ) 12. Nxd4 $1 { This position reminds me a bit of the Steinitz defense 3...d6, only that now Black's bishop is on a7 and not on e7, which means that our pin against the knight on f6 is even stronger. } ( 12. cxd4 Bg4 $1 { Blak has a good counterplay. } ) 12... Bd7 13. Nd2 $14 { White has a typical, slightly better position. For example: } 13... Re8 14. Qf3 g5 15. Bg3 Bg4 16. Qd3 Qd7 17. h3 Bh5 { was played in the game Urazayev-Nabaty, 2023. White's best would have been } 18. Nf5 $14 Kh7 19. Bh2 $1 { [%cal Gg2g4] A strong move, with the idea to face } 19... Bg6 { with } 20. g4 $16 ) 11. Bb3 d6 12. Bd5 $1 Bd7 13. cxd4 $1 ( 13. Nxd4 $6 Nxd4 14. Bxa8 $2 Ne6 $15 { Black was already better in Yakubboev-Pranesh, 2024. } ) 13... g5 14. Bxc6 Bxc6 15. Qc1 $1 { [%cal Gc1c6,Gc1g5] a very important move. We attack both the bishop on c6 and the pawn on g5. } 15... Bd7 16. Nxg5 hxg5 17. Qxg5+ Kh7 18. Qxf6 $14 { This is a logical improvement over the Miron-Pranesh game. } ( 18. d5 { Miron-Pranesh } 18... Bd4 $1 19. Qd2 Be5 20. f4 Nxe4 $1 21. Bxd8 Nxd2 22. fxe5 Nxb1 23. Be7 Bf5 $1 24. Bxf8 Rxf8 $11 { Looks like a draw. } ) 18... Qxf6 19. Bxf6 Kg6 $1 { [%cal Ra7d4] Black has to play it with the idea of gaining the pawn on d4. } 20. Bh4 Bxd4 21. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3d5] We are ready to play Nd5, so Black's best move by far is } 21... Be6 $1 { but after } 22. Red1 c5 23. Rd2 { [%cal Yd2b2,Gc3e2] We defend the pawn on b2 and are ready for Ne2. } 23... Bc4 $1 24. Ne2 Bxe2 25. Rxe2 $14 { The engine evaluates +0,50, and it's clear that Black will suffer in this pawn-down endgame. } *

