1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5 6. c3 b5 {In the previous chapter, we analyzed 6...00. Now, we will analyze the main 6...b5 move. By playing this move order, Black wants to play the main Arkhangelsk variation (5...b5 6.Bb3 Bc5) but has excluded all Nxe5 variations.} 7. Bc2 {But now we can immediately retreat our bishop on c2! If Black plays in the Classical spirit with d6, then we have an improved version because the bishop on c2 is better placed, but Black can now play the critical 7...d5.} ({if we play} 7. Bb3 {then after} d6 {We transpose into a variation that we do NOT play against the 5...b5 6.Bb3 Bc5 move order.}) 7... d6 {[%csl Gc2] This is not critical. Black builds the main Arkhangelsk set-up, but our bishop is now better placed on c2 (in the main Arkhangelsk, we have the same position but with our bishop on b3) . Let's see some key differences:} 8. d4 Bb6 (8... Ba7 {Normally, Black's bishop is better placed on b6, but the only justification for playing Ba7 could be that after} 9. a4 {Black's pawn on b5 is not hanging now, and Black can play another move like Bg4, or just 00.} Bg4 (9... O-O {Looks logical, but Black experiences some problems after} 10. d5 $1 Ne7 11. axb5 axb5 12. Be3 $1 c5 13. c4 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3]} bxc4 (13... b4 14. Nh4 $16 {[%csl Ra7] White is better, mainly because Black's bishop on a7 is passive.}) 14. Nfd2 $16 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gb1c3] Nc3-Nxc4 next, and White is better from the strategic point of view.}) (9... exd4 10. cxd4 Bg4 11. axb5 axb5 12. Be3 O-O 13. Nc3 Bb6 (13... b4 14. Ne2 Bb6 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 16. Qd3 $16 {[%csl Rb6,Gd4,Ge4] White has a strong center, and Black's bishop on b6 is bad.}) 14. Rxa8 Qxa8 15. Nxb5 $16 {Black had no enough compensation for the missing pawn in Caruana-Godena, 2011.}) 10. axb5 axb5 {Was recently tried by Adams from the Black side.} 11. Ra6 $1 {It's a bit awkward for Black to defend the knight.} Bb6 12. Rxa8 Qxa8 13. h3 $1 {It's very important to force Black to take a choice immediately.} (13. d5 $6 {Was played in Willow-Adams, but after} Ne7 $1 14. h3 Bd7 $13 {[%csl Yb5][%cal Gd7b5] Black has a very comfortable position.}) 13... Bh5 (13... Bxf3 $2 {Crticial, but bad:} 14. Qxf3 exd4 15. e5 $1 {[%cal Gf3a8]} dxe5 16. Bg5 $18 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gc2e4] We have Bxf6-gxf6-Be4 ideas, and Black is lost.}) (13... Bd7 {Now, that the d4 pawn is no longer under pressure, we will play without d5.} 14. Na3 $16 {[%csl Rb5] White is better.}) 14. d5 $1 {Only now, that Black's bishop is already on h5, we will go for d5.} Ne7 15. Na3 $16 {Compared to the game Willow-Adams, here Black's bishop cannot go back to d7, which means that the b5 pawn is very weak.}) 9. a4 Bb7 {Also here, the bishop on c2 plays a very important role, as the e4 pawn is now defended:} (9... Rb8 {This is Black's main continuation in the main position when our bishop is still on b3, but here it is not good!} 10. axb5 axb5 11. Na3 O-O 12. Nxb5 Bg4 {Imagine this same position with our bishop still on b3. In that situation, White's main and best move is Bc2 back, and there are more than 500 games played. Here, we just have a full tempo up, which is obviously crucial in this type of positions:} 13. d5 (13. Z0 {if it's Black to move (like in the main Arkhangelsk) , then after} Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nh5 $13 {Qh4 next, and the game is very unclear.}) 13... Ne7 14. Na3 $16 {[%cal Gh2h3,Ga3c4] h3 or Nc4 next. White is much better.}) (9... Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. d5 $1 Ne7 {[%csl Gc2,Ge4][%cal Gc2e4] Imagine the same position but with White's bishop on b3, like in the main Arkhangelsk. In that situation, White needs to spend an important tempo to protect the e4 pawn, but here we can continue concretely} 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14. Na3 $16 {[%csl Rb5] Where Black will very probably lose the b5 pawn. As you can see, also after 9...Bg4, White's bishop on c2 is a big improvement compared to the main lines with the bishop on b3.}) 10. d5 Ne7 11. Bg5 {This variation is not possible when our bishop is still on b3 because Black would just play Nxe4.} Ng6 12. a5 $14 (12. axb5 {Is White's most common continuation, but after} axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 $1 14. Na3 h6 $1 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Nxb5 Rg8 $44 {It seems that Black has a very good compensation.}) 12... Ba7 13. c4 $1 {This is my recommendation. Black needs to immediately take an important structural decision.} h6 $1 {This is Black's best continuation, and now we have two interesting directions:} (13... b4 $2 14. Ba4+ Kf8 15. Nbd2 $16 {[%cal Gg5e3] Be3 next, and White has a big advantage.}) (13... bxc4 $6 14. Ba4+ Kf8 15. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Gc2c4] Qxc4 next, with a good positional advantage.}) (13... O-O 14. cxb5 axb5 15. b4 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3] Nc3 next, and White is better.}) 14. Be3 $5 (14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. cxb5 O-O $1 (15... axb5 $6 16. b4 $16 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gb1c3,Gc2d3] We will continue with Nc3-Bd3, putting a lot of pressure against Black's probably lost b5 pawn.}) 16. Nc3 Bc8 $1 {This is Black's best defence, according to the engine. White is still better, but Black gets some compensation.}) 14... Bxe3 15. fxe3 $36 {[%cal Gf1f8] We open the 'f' file, and our position looks very interesting. The engine evaluates +0,45. For example:} bxc4 (15... O-O 16. cxb5 axb5 17. b4 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3] Nc3 next.}) 16. Nc3 O-O 17. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gd2c4,Yb2b4,Yb4b5] Nxc4 next, with a good positional edge. Black's problem is that his a6 pawn is vulnerable, and we will always have b4-b5 ideas.} *

