1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5 6. c3 b5 7. Bc2 d5 $1 { This is Black's most concrete and serious continuation. Now, you really need to memorize some lines. } 8. a4 $1 { This is White's most interesting continuation. } ( 8. d4 { Is White's most common continuation, but after } 8... dxe4 { It's very difficult to find something interesting. For example: } 9. Nxe5 ( 9. dxc5 Qxd1 10. Bxd1 exf3 11. Bxf3 e4 $11 ) 9... Nxe5 10. dxc5 Qe7 $11 ) 8... dxe4 $1 ( 8... b4 $6 9. d4 { The inclusion of the moves 8. a4 b4 is in White's favor. } 9... dxe4 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxc5 $16 { [%csl Rb4] The difference in this line is that now, the pawn is attacked on b4. For instance, Black cannot play Qe7, which is his best move in the same position, without the inclusion of a4-b4. } ) ( 8... Rb8 { As mentioned in 8...b4, the inclusion of a4+Rb8 goes in White's favor: } 9. d4 $1 dxe4 10. dxc5 Qxd1 11. Bxd1 exf3 12. Bxf3 e4 13. Be2 $14 { [%csl Rb5][%cal Ga1a8] We can play against Black's pawn on b5 and eventually open the 'a' file. } ) 9. axb5 { Now, Black has two very serious continuations: exf3 and Bg4. } 9... exf3 { From now the game gets quite forced till move 15. } ( 9... Bg4 { Is a very important continuation, and it will be analyzed separately. } ) 10. Qxf3 e4 $1 { Black must play this move, otherwise White will regain the piece. } 11. Bxe4 Ne5 $1 { only move for Black. } 12. Qe2 O-O 13. d4 $1 ( 13. Bxa8 $2 Nd3 $15 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gf8e8] Black is already better. } ) 13... Bg4 14. Qc2 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 { This is the critical position of the 9...exf3 variation. Black has now two possible continuations: } 15... Bd7 { This is a very serious move, and Sindarov played it twice with great results. } ( 15... Nf3+ { Is Black's most common continuation, and it will be analyzed separately. } ) 16. bxa6 Bb5 $1 17. Qxe5 Bxf1 18. Kxf1 Ba7 { We have three pawns and a knight for the exchange, which normally is good for us, but the position is still very concrete. } 19. Qf5 $14 { This prophylactic move against Re8 its White's only chance to fight for an advantage. } ( 19. Nd2 $6 { Is a normal-looking move, and it was played by MVL against Sindarov, but after } 19... c5 $13 { Black's position is objectively fine, and Black won that game. } ) ( 19. b4 { Was played by Suleymanli against Sinadrov. White's idea is to stop c5, but Black is fine after } 19... Re8 $1 { Where it's actually White who needs to play precisely. } 20. Qh5 $1 { only move for White. } ( 20. Qf5 $2 Bxd4 $19 { Black was winning in Syleymanli-Sindarov, 2023. } ) 20... Bxd4 21. Qd1 $11 ) ( 19. g3 $6 { is a bad move order because of } 19... Qd7 $15 ) 19... c5 { As we have seen, this is Black's standard idea. } ( 19... Re8 20. g3 c5 { transposes. } ) 20. d5 $1 Re8 ( 20... Qh4 $2 21. Kg1 $1 Rfe8 22. g3 $16 ) 21. g3 $1 { We give a safe square for our king, and Black must be very precise. } 21... c4 $1 { Only move for Black. Otherwise, he is worse. } ( 21... Qe7 $2 { Is natural, but after } 22. Kg2 $16 { White's position is already seriously better. In general, if we manage to defend from Black's concrete ideas, we have serious winning chances. } ) 22. Na3 $1 Qa5 $3 { Black's only defence. } ( 22... Qe7 23. Kg2 $16 { Is similar to 21...Qe7. } ) 23. Nc2 Qb5 24. Nb4 g6 $1 { Again, only move! As you see, Black's position is very risky, and the only way for him not to lose immediately is to follow many of the engine's only move recommendations. } 25. Qf4 Bc5 26. Nc6 Rxa6 27. Rxa6 Qxa6 28. Ne5 f6 $1 29. Qxc4 Qxc4+ 30. Nxc4 Rd8 $1 31. Ke2 Rxd5 32. b4 $36 { The engine thinks that Black holds, but in a practical game, it's very easy to win with White. Also, Black had to find an incredible amount of only moves to get here! } *

