1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5 6. c3 b5 7. Bc2 d5 $1 { This is Black's most concrete and serious continuation. Now, you really need to memorize some lines. } 8. a4 $1 { This is White's most interesting continuation. } 8... dxe4 $1 9. axb5 { Now, Black has two very serious continuations: exf3 and Bg4. } 9... exf3 { From now the game gets quite forced till move 15. } 10. Qxf3 e4 $1 { Black must play this move, otherwise White will regain the piece. } 11. Bxe4 Ne5 $1 { only move for Black. } 12. Qe2 O-O 13. d4 $1 ( 13. Bxa8 $2 Nd3 $15 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gf8e8] Black is already better. } ) 13... Bg4 14. Qc2 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 { This is the critical position of the 9...exf3 variation. } 15... Nf3+ { Before Sindarov's 15...Bd7, this was considered Black's main direction. Black goes for a very long forced line, which we need to follow and only then evaluate the position. } 16. gxf3 Bh3 17. dxc5 $1 ( 17. Re1 $6 Bd6 $40 { Black has the initiative. } ) 17... Bxf1 18. Kxf1 Qd1+ 19. Qe1 Qxf3 20. Be3 axb5 21. Rxa8 Rxa8 22. Nd2 Qh1+ 23. Ke2 Qxh2 { From move 15, all of this was forced! What's going on here? We have a knight and a bishop for rook and pawn. Our king is now safe in the center because Black doesn't have too many pieces to attack it. In general, our plan will be to play against Black's queenside pawns, while Black should push the 'h' pawn sooner or later. We cannot stop yet because from this position, a lot of games have been played, and we need to understand what's going on. } 24. Nf3 Qh3 25. Qd1 { [%cal Gd1d5] This is a standard move. White activates his queen and wants to play Qd5. } 25... Qe6 $1 { The only move for Black. Otherwise, White plays Qd5 and gets a winning position. } ( 25... h6 $4 { Is a huge mistake, because after } 26. Qd5 Ra1 27. Bd2 $1 Qf1+ 28. Ke3 $18 { Black doesn't have more threats, and White can easily develop his initiative (Nd4 next, for example) . According to the engine, the evaluation is +3,00. } ) 26. Qd3 $1 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Ye6c4,Gd3c4] We prevent Qc4+. } ( 26. Nd4 Qc4+ 27. Qd3 Qxc5 28. Qxb5 Qxb5+ 29. Nxb5 Rb8 $11 { Black equalized in the games Adams-Schroeder, 2016. } ) 26... c6 $1 { Again, Black needs to find this move; otherwise, his position will be lost. Now, White has a lot of tries. } ( 26... Qc4 $2 27. Qxc4 bxc4 28. Bf4 $18 { White's position is mathematically winning. } ) ( 26... Qb3 $2 27. Ng5 $1 Qc4 28. Qxc4 bxc4 29. Nf3 { Compared to 26...Qc4, here Black has an extra tempo, but it's still not enough to make a draw: } 29... f6 ( 29... Ra2 { Pichot-Yu, 2018. } 30. Bf4 $1 Rxb2+ 31. Kf1 $18 { [%csl Rc7] Black will lose the c7 pawn and the game. } ( 31. Ke3 $2 Rc2 $11 ) ) 30. Nd4 $14 { [%cal Ge3f4,Gd4b5] White's only winning move. } ( 30. Bf4 c6 31. Nd2 Ra4 32. Ke3 h5 $11 { Black gets a good counterplay. } ) 30... Kf7 31. Nb5 c6 32. Nd6+ Ke6 33. Kf3 $3 ( 33. Nxc4 $2 Ra1 $1 { and it's a draw! } 34. Kf3 Rg1 $11 { [%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] } ) 33... Ra1 34. Kg2 $1 { Black is not in time to cut our king along the 'g' file, and after } 34... Ra4 35. Bd4 $18 { White's position is objectively winning. } ) 27. Ng5 $14 { This is my recommendation. It was never tried in practice, and I think it poses the maximum amount of problems to the opponent. } ( 27. Nd4 $5 { This was the recommendation of Ivan Cheparinov. } 27... Qg4+ $1 ( 27... Qd5 $2 28. Nf5 { This is White's idea. } 28... Qe6 29. Kf3 Re8 30. Ng3 $16 { White is slowly consolidating the position, so White is better. The pawn on c6 is weak and will be a target in the long run. } ) 28. Kd2 { Black has two possible continuations: } 28... Rd8 ( 28... Ra1 29. Qe2 ( 29. Kc2 h5 $1 { Black starts a counterplay. } 30. f3 Qh4 31. Qe2 Qh1 $13 ) 29... Qxe2+ 30. Kxe2 Ra6 $11 { The rook on a6 is passive now since it's stuck defending the c6-pawn. White can try the idea of Kd3, c4, and after the exchange ...bxc4 Kxc4, White can push b4-b5 in order to create a passed pawn. The position is around equal, but only White can be better. } ) 29. Qb1 $5 { [%cal Gb1h1] White wants to play Qh1, attacking the pawn on c6 and slowing down Black's advancement of the h-pawn. } 29... Qh5 $1 { preventing Qh1. } 30. Qe4 Qxc5 31. Ke1 { [%csl Rc6] } 31... Qa7 ( 31... Qd5 $5 32. Qxd5 Rxd5 33. Nxc6 Kf8 34. Kf1 $11 { [%cal Gf1g2] Cheparinov continues the analysis. I agree with him that the endgame is playable, but most likely it will end in a draw. } ) 32. Kf1 { Our king goes to g2. } 32... Qa4 33. Kg2 ( 33. Qxc6 Qd1+ 34. Kg2 Qg4+ $11 { Ends in a perpetual. } ) 33... c5 34. b3 Qa8 35. Qxa8 Rxa8 36. Nxb5 Rc8 ( 36... Rb8 { should also be a draw. } ) 37. Nd6 Rb8 $1 38. Bxc5 Rxb3 $11 { 27.Nd4 suggested by Cheparinov is definitely a try, but I was not fully satisfied with it. } ) ( 27. Qd6 { This is White's most common move in practice. } 27... Qc4+ 28. Kd2 b4 $11 { White tried different moves, but Black is fine everywhere in more than one way. } ) 27... Qg4+ $1 { only move. } 28. Kd2 Qh5 $1 ( 28... Qh4 $2 29. Qd7 $18 ) 29. Kc2 $5 { This is an interesting move. What is our idea? Just to wait Black's reaction, because it's not so easy for him to find a move. } ( 29. Qd6 Qg4 30. Qxc6 $2 Rd8+ $19 ) ( 29. Qe4 $2 Rd8+ $19 ) ( 29. Bf4 $5 { [%cal Gd3e4,Gf4d6,Ya8d8] This move is useful because we will always have Ke3 against Rd8+. Now, Black is fine only after two moves: } 29... Qh4 $1 { This is more human than 29...Re8. } ( 29... Re8 $1 { is also fine. Black prevents Qe4, but Re8 is a difficult move for a human. } ) 30. Qf3 h6 $1 { Black's best, but it's difficult to find. } ( 30... Rd8+ $6 31. Kc2 $14 ) 31. Ne4 ( 31. Nxf7 Rf8 $1 32. Bg3 Qe7 33. Nxh6+ gxh6 34. Qxc6 Qg5+ 35. Kd3 Qf5+ 36. Qe4 Qxc5 37. Qg6+ $11 ) 31... Ra4 $1 32. b3 Ra2+ 33. Kd3 Qd8+ 34. Nd6 Qf6 35. Qxc6 Qxf4 36. Qe8+ Kh7 37. Qe4+ Qxe4+ 38. Kxe4 { Black can make a draw with only moves: } 38... Re2+ $1 39. Kf3 ( 39. Kd5 Rd2+ $1 40. Kc6 h5 $1 41. Kxb5 h4 42. Ne4 $11 ) 39... Re6 $1 40. Nxb5 $11 { That's why 29.Bf4 might be a good practical try. } ) 29... Re8 { [%cal Gf7f6] This is probably the most natural move for a human, because Black prepares f6. } ( 29... Qg6 $2 30. Qxg6 hxg6 31. c4 $18 ) ( 29... Qh1 $6 30. c4 $16 ) ( 29... f6 $2 30. Ne6 $16 ) ( 29... Rf8 { This may be a normal move if Black just waits what we want to do. } 30. c4 $5 bxc4 31. Qxc4 h6 32. Ne4 Qf5 33. Kd2 h5 34. Nd6 Qf3 35. Qd4 $13 { [%cal Gd4e5,Ge3d4] Maybe Black's position is not so easy to play from the practical point of view. We can slowly prepare some ideas like Qe5-Bd4. } ) 30. Ne4 { [%cal Ge4d6] Black has only two moves not to get a lost position: Qg4 and Qf3. } ( 30. Qd7 Qe2+ $11 ) ( 30. b4 $5 Ra8 31. Kb2 Qh1 32. Bc1 $13 { deserves attention. } ) 30... Qg4 $1 ( 30... Qf3 { is not losing, but White has chances after } 31. Nd2 Qg4 32. Qd6 $14 ) 31. Nd6 Rd8 $1 { Only move. } ( 31... Re5 $2 32. c4 $1 bxc4 33. Qxc4 $16 ) 32. Qf5 Qe2+ $1 ( 32... Qxf5+ $2 33. Nxf5 $18 { White has a winning endgame. } ) 33. Bd2 f6 $1 { You can see how difficult it is to play from the Black's side. f6 is another only move for him. } ( 33... Qe7 $2 34. Be3 $18 { White's position is already winning. } ) 34. f3 { [%cal Gf5h5] We have a lot of ideas with White, but I like this one. We prepare Qh5, but it's also difficult for Black to find a move. } ( 34. Qh3 { also interesting, and Black is fine only after the following 2 moves: } 34... Qe5 $1 35. Be3 Qd5 $1 36. Bd4 { now Black can choose, maybe the simplest is } 36... h5 $11 ) 34... h6 $3 ( 34... Qe7 $2 { Natural but losing: } 35. b4 $16 { [%cal Gc3c4] c4 next. } ) 35. Qg6 Rd7 $1 { Here I didn't find anything concrete, you can move a bit the queen, for example: } ( 35... Qxf3 $6 36. Bxh6 Qe2+ 37. Bd2 $14 ) 36. Qg4 Rd8 37. Qf5 Ra8 $11 { But Black is objectively fine. CONCLUSIONS: The key position of this chapter emerges after 26...c6. In my view, 27.Ng5!? is Whiteâ€™s most promising attempt. Although the engine indicates that Blackâ€™s position is technically defensible, 27.Ng5!? (a novelty) presents Black with challenging moves that are difficult to navigate, especially in practical play. Generally, thereâ€™s no need to worry if Black theoretically holds; with White, you have many options, and itâ€™s nearly impossible for Black to prepare for everything. This guarantees you a rich and playable game! } *

