 the same position, with Black's rook on f8 and not on a8, Black would have continued wth Qg6+, but here it's check! } 20... Rxe8 21. Bf7 $18 { [%csl Gg6][%cal Yd6g6] We prevent Qg6+, and White's position is winning. } ) 17. Re3 $1 Nh5 18. Rg5 $1 { We prevent Qg6+. } ( 18. Rxe4 { This was good against 16...Rfe8, but not here: } 18... f5 $1 19. Bb3+ Kh8 20. Rxe8 Qg6+ $19 { This is the big difference between 16...Rfe8 and 16...Rae8. } ) 18... Qh6 $1 { Again only move. This is probably the starting position of the 9...Bg4 variation. As you have seen, both sides had to make many only moves to arrive here. } 19. f4 $1 ( 19. Rg3 { This is interesting from the practical point of view, but objectively Black equalizes. You can use this alternative if you are scared of studying all the beautiful lines arising after 19.f4! } 19... Nxg3 20. hxg3 exf3 21. Qxf3 Re6 $1 { Black has to find this strong move, and the position is objectively balanced. However, Cheparinov offers a new idea for White: } 22. Bd3 $14 Rd8 $1 { Black has to find also this move. } ( 22... Rfe8 $6 23. Bc4 $16 ) 23. Be2 Qg6 $1 { [%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Yh3g4] Black prepares h5-h4 or h5-Bg4. } 24. Na3 h5 $1 25. Qxh5 Rxe3 $1 26. Qxg6 Rxe2 $11 { Black had to be very precise, but this position is a draw. } ) 19... Nxf4 20. Reg3 $1 { This is White's critical continuation. } ( 20. Rgg3 { This is the recommendation of Ivan Cheparinov. } 20... f5 21. d4 Bg4 22. Qf1 Nh5 23. Re1 { He likes the position for White, but he doesn't offer: } 23... Qxc6 24. Bf4 Kh8 $13 { A very strong continuation for Black, and the game is open to all three results. You need to understand that the engines are becoming stronger and stronger, and what was interesting 2 years ago, may have a totally different value today. } ) 20... f5 { [%cal Gh3g4] Black prepares Bg4. } ( 20... g6 $2 { Would be a huge mistake, after } 21. d4 e3 22. Re5 $18 { White is winning. } ) 21. Rxg7+ { This is a critical position for determining whether 9...Bg4 holds up or is truly refuted. While youâ€™re welcome to stop here if you prefer a more general overview, Iâ€™ve prepared two extra chapters for ambitious players looking to dive deeper into the concrete variations. You can explore these chapters out of curiosity, or study them thoroughly if you're aiming for a comprehensive, in-depth understanding. } 21... Qxg7 { Will be analyzed in Chapter 11. } ( 21... Kh8 $14 { Will be analyed in Chapter 10. } ) *

