{ Welcome, dear chess players, to this in-depth chapter. You might wonder why Iâ€™ve dedicated a complete chapter to 21...Kh8 and another to 21...Qxg7+. There are three reasons. First, the amount of material for each move is substantial enough to warrant a full chapter. Second, in my years of experience as a "Second" (opening trainer) , Iâ€™ve observed that players often struggle to memorize extensive files with countless variations. Focusing on each key position in its own chapter makes it significantly easier to retain. Lastly, by organizing the material into separate, concrete files, youâ€™ll find it much simpler to revisit and deepen your understanding on your own. If 21...Kh8 were buried as a minor sideline, it might never get the attention it deserves! } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5 6. c3 b5 7. Bc2 d5 8. a4 dxe4 9. axb5 Bg4 10. bxc6 exf3 11. gxf3 Bh3 12. Re1 O-O 13. Ra5 $1 Qd6 14. b4 $1 Bxf2+ $1 15. Kxf2 e4 { [%cal Yd6h2] } 16. Kg1 $1 Rae8 $1 17. Re3 $1 Nh5 18. Rg5 $1 Qh6 $1 19. f4 $1 Nxf4 20. Reg3 $1 f5 { [%cal Gh3g4] } 21. Rxg7+ Kh8 $14 { This move has never been played, but the game is very forced, and interesting. For example, Cheparinov mentions that he doens't like 20.Reg3 because of 21...Kh8. } 22. c4 $1 { [%csl Rh8][%cal Gc1b2] Our idea is Bb2, and to play against Black's king on h8. } 22... Qf6 $1 { Black prevents Bb2, and it's is only move not to lose immediately. } 23. Qe1 $1 { Prophylactic move against Bg4. Now, it's a game of memorization. If you memorize everything, you will have very big chances to win the game. If you don't feel comfortable in memorizing a lot of forced lines, then you can opt for the safer 19.Rg1, accepting that if Black knowd everything it will be an immediate draw. } ( 23. Rxc7 $6 { Would be less precise, because Black can play } 23... Rg8 $11 ) 23... Bg4 24. Rxc7 Nh3+ $1 ( 24... Ne2+ $2 { This move is losing, but White needs to know: } 25. Kf1 h5 ( 25... Nxg3+ 26. Qxg3 $18 ) 26. Qf2 $1 e3 ( 26... Nxc1 27. Nc3 h4 28. Re3 $18 ) 27. Rxe3 f4 28. Re4 $1 Nxc1 29. Qc5 Bh3+ 30. Ke1 Bf5 ( 30... Bg4 31. Rh7+ $1 Kg8 32. Rxh5 $18 ) 31. Nc3 $1 f3 32. Qe3 Bxe4 33. Bxe4 ( 33. Nxe4 $2 Qg6 $19 ) 33... Ne2 34. Rh7+ $1 Kg8 35. Rd7 $18 ) 25. Kg2 Nf4+ 26. Kf2 Nd3+ ( 26... Ne2 27. Kf1 $1 { transposes in 24...Ne2+. } ) 27. Bxd3 exd3 { and now comes the very beautiful key idea: } 28. Re7 $3 Rxe7 29. Bb2 Rxe1 30. Bxf6+ Rxf6 31. Kxe1 Rxc6 32. c5 { Black needs to defend a very dangerous endgame. In a practical game, it's much easier to win it for White than to draw it for Black, in my opinion. Now, Black's only two not losing moves are a5 or Re6+. } 32... a5 ( 32... Re6+ 33. Re3 f4 $1 34. Rxe6 Bxe6 { The first moves of this endgame are forced, as Black needs to bring his king closer to the 'c' pawn: } 35. Na3 ( 35. Kf2 Bd5 $11 ) 35... Kg7 36. c6 Kf8 37. Kf2 Ke7 38. Kf3 Kd6 39. b5 axb5 40. Nxb5+ { Everything was very logical so far. Also this endgame is a draw, but Black needs to play extremely well: } 40... Kc5 $1 ( 40... Kxc6 $4 41. Nd4+ Kd5 42. Nxe6 Kxe6 43. Kxf4 $18 { The pawn endgame is winning for White. } ) 41. Nc3 Kxc6 { If you check with the engine, it's 0.00, but I think Black still needs to play very well. For example: } 42. Ne4 h6 { logical move, against Ng5. } ( 42... Kd5 43. Kxf4 Kd4 44. Nf6 h6 { transposes to 42...h6. } ) ( 42... Bf7 { This is another possible defence for Black. } 43. Kxf4 Bg6 44. Ke5 Kd7 $1 45. Nf6+ Ke7 46. Nd5+ Kf8 $1 ( 46... Kf7 $4 { loses to: } 47. Nf4 $18 ) 47. Kf6 Be4 $11 { 0.00, but maybe White can try somehow. It's very possible that Black will have some only move defense at some point, which might be difficult or not. } ) 43. Kxf4 Kd5 $1 { only move. } 44. Nf6+ Kd4 ( 44... Kd6 $4 { would be immediately losing because of } 45. Ng4 $18 ) 45. h4 { This is a very good endgame exercises. Black to play and makes a draw with only one move: } ( 45. Ng4 Bxg4 46. Kxg4 Ke4 $11 ) 45... Bb3 $3 { [%cal Gb3d1] The bishop has to go to d1, to protect the h5 pawn. } 46. Ng4 h5 $11 { I didn't check further, but I think White can pose some other questions. } ) 33. b5 Rxc5 34. Nc3 { Black needs to find now the strong } 34... Rc4 $1 ( 34... Kg7 $2 { bad move order for Black. } 35. b6 $18 ) 35. Rxd3 Kg7 $1 { It's very important for Black to activate the king. } ( 35... Rb4 $2 { logical, but bad: } 36. Rd7 $16 { [%csl Rh8] Black's king needs to stay on the 8th rank. } ) 36. Rd7+ { White has also other tries, but this looks the most natural one. } 36... Kf6 37. Ra7 Bf3 $1 { only move, with the idea Rh4. } 38. Rxa5 Rh4 39. Kf2 Be4 40. Kg1 Rg4+ 41. Kf1 Rh4 42. b6 $11 { Objectively a draw, but Black needs still to play many only moves. I suggest you to analyze very well this position because it is very interesting if you like endgames. As you have seen, 21...Kh8 objectively holds, but Black needs to be extremely well prepares until move 40 or more! We cannot for sure call this a forced draw :) } *

