{Welcome, dear chess players, to this in-depth chapter. You might wonder why I’ve dedicated a complete chapter to 21...Kh8 and another to 21...Qxg7+. There are three reasons. First, the amount of material for each move is substantial enough to warrant a full chapter. Second, in my years of experience as a "Second" (opening trainer) , I’ve observed that players often struggle to memorize extensive files with countless variations. Focusing on each key position in its own chapter makes it significantly easier to retain. Lastly, by organizing the material into separate, concrete files, you’ll find it much simpler to revisit and deepen your understanding on your own. If 21...Kh8 were buried as a minor sideline, it might never get the attention it deserves!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5 6. c3 b5 7. Bc2 d5 8. a4 dxe4 9. axb5 Bg4 10. bxc6 exf3 11. gxf3 Bh3 12. Re1 O-O 13. Ra5 $1 Qd6 14. b4 $1 Bxf2+ $1 15. Kxf2 e4 {[%cal Yd6h2]} 16. Kg1 $1 Rae8 $1 17. Re3 $1 Nh5 18. Rg5 $1 Qh6 $1 19. f4 $1 Nxf4 20. Reg3 $1 f5 {[%cal Gh3g4]} 21. Rxg7+ Qxg7 {This move has been played in all the seven games that have reached this position. The arising variations are extremely entrataining.} 22. Rxg7+ Kxg7 {We have queen and bishop against two rooks, but our king is not safe. Black had a huge counterplay, but we are still fighting for the advantage.} 23. Qe1 $1 {[%cal Ge1g3] Our big threat is Qg3+, and Black has three possible continuations.} Rg8 $5 $146 {This move was never tried, but it's also an interesting option for Black.} (23... e3 {This move was tried by the big opening theoretician GM Wojtaszek.} 24. dxe3 Rf6 25. Kf2 $1 {Useful prophylactic move.} Rg6 26. Nd2 Rg2+ 27. Kf3 Ng6 {[%cal Gg6e5] Black's threat is Ne5+, which would be almost mate.} 28. e4 $1 {[%cal Gf3e3] We free the e3 square for our king.} f4 $14 {Black doesn't allow Ke3.} (28... Ne5+ $4 {Was played by Wojtaszek, but it is immediately losing.} 29. Ke3 f4+ 30. Kxf4 Ng4 31. e5 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf4e4] Only move, but it is winning.} Nxe5 (31... Rf8+ 32. Ke4 $18) 32. Qxe5+ Rxe5 33. Kxe5 Rxh2 34. Be4 $18 {Moranda-Wojtaszek, 2021.}) 29. Qh1 $1 {[%cal Gh1g2] Our threat is Qxg2. Other moves are also possible, but this is the most challenging one.} Kf6 {Black prepares against Qxg2 and makes the idea Nh4+ possible.} (29... Rg5 $2 30. Kf2 $1 Nh4 31. Bd1 Rg2+ 32. Ke1 $18) (29... Kh6 {[%cal Ge8f8,Gg6e5] Black has Rf8-Ne5+ idea.} 30. Qxg2 (30. Bb3 {was our move against 29...Kh6, but after} Rf8 $36 {[%cal Gg6e5] Ne5+ is a strong idea, and Black already has the initiative.}) 30... Nh4+ 31. Kxf4 Nxg2+ 32. Kg3 Rg8+ $1 33. Kf2 $1 (33. Kxh3 Nf4+ 34. Kh4 Ng2+ $11 {is a draw.}) 33... Nf4 34. Kf3 Ne6 35. Nb3+ Kg7 36. Nd4 Kf6 37. Nxe6 Bxe6 38. Bf4 $14 {Black's defensive task is very challenging, but the engine holds with the best moves.}) 30. Bb3 {[%cal Ge8f8,Gd2c4] Black doesn't have Rf8-Nh4+ idea.} (30. c4 $5 {deserves attention. In general, White has many options, and it's almost impossible for Black to analyse all of them.}) (30. Qxg2 {I don't like this now, because after} Nh4+ 31. Kxf4 Nxg2+ 32. Kg3 Rg8+ 33. Kf2 Nf4 $11 {[%csl Gf6] Black's king on f6 is better placed than h6.}) 30... h5 $1 {Only move for Black.} ({To understand the move 30...h5 we can check what happens if it's our move again:} 30... Z0 31. Nc4 Rd8 32. e5+ Kf5 33. Bxf4 Nxf4 34. Ne3+ Kxe5 35. Qa1 $18 {White is winning, because Black doesn't have Bg4+.}) 31. Bd5 {[%cal Gc3c4,Gc1b2] Our idea is c4-Bb2+.} (31. Nc4 {This move illustrates the value of 30...h5:} Rd8 32. e5+ Kf5 33. Bxf4 Nxf4 34. Ne3+ Kxe5 35. Qa1 {In the same position with Black's pawn on h7, White is winning. But here Black has mate in 3:} Bg4+ $1 36. Nxg4+ hxg4+ 37. Ke3 Re2#) 31... Rg5 $1 {[%cal Gh3g2] Black prevents Qxg2 and prepares Bg2+.} (31... Re5 32. Qxg2 Nh4+ 33. Kf2 Bxg2 34. c4 $14 {[%cal Gc1b2] Bb2 next and our bishops are too strong, while Black's position is extremely dangerous.}) 32. Kf2 Ne5 33. Bc4 $1 {important move against Nd3+.} Rg2+ 34. Qxg2 Bxg2 35. Kxg2 Nxc4 36. Nxc4 Rxe4 $11 {White can try Na5 or Na3. The endgame looks lost for Black, but the engine holds with precise moves.}) (23... Rf6 {This is Black's most popular continuation.} 24. Qe3 $1 {[%csl Ge1] We free the e1 square for our king.} Rg6+ 25. Kf2 Rg4 $1 {[%cal Ge8e6,Ge6g6] Only move for Black. He prepares Re6-Reg6, and doesn't allow Ke1 because of the Ng2+ idea.} (25... Rg2+ $4 {Is a decisive mistake:} 26. Ke1 Rg4 (26... Re2+ 27. Qxe2 Nxe2 28. Kxe2 $18 {The endgame is winning for White.}) 27. Kd1 {Black's position was already lost in Iniyan-Adhiban, 2022. We can check some more moves to see how the game finished:} Bf1 28. Ba3 {[%cal Gd1c1] The king will be very safe on c1 (eventually on b2 later) .} Nd5 29. Qd4+ Nf6 30. Qa7 Kg6 31. Kc1 $18 {Iniyan-Adhiban, 2022.}) 26. Bb2 {[%cal Gc3c4] We prepare c4+.} (26. Na3 {Was also tried by White, but the game is more difficult to understand compared to 26.Bb2.}) (26. d4 $5 Rg2+ 27. Ke1 Re2+ 28. Qxe2 Nxe2 29. Kxe2 e3 $1 30. Na3 f4 31. Nc4 Bg4+ $11) 26... Re6 {This is Black's main idea of the position, but other moves like Kf8!? were also possible.} 27. c4+ Kf7 $1 {Only move for Black. Other moves are losing.} (27... Kf8 $2 28. Qc5+ Ke8 29. Be5 $18) 28. b5 $1 {We push forward our queenside pawns, that may become scary for Black. Now, Black has a lot of possible move to reach the same position:} Rg2+ (28... Nd3+ 29. Bxd3 Rg2+ 30. Ke1 exd3 {transposes in 28...Rg2+.}) (28... axb5 29. cxb5 Nd3+ 30. Bxd3 Rg2+ 31. Ke1 exd3 {also transposes in 28...Rg2+ after} 32. Be5 Re2+ 33. Qxe2 dxe2 34. Bxc7 {trans}) 29. Ke1 Nd3+ 30. Bxd3 exd3 31. Be5 Re2+ 32. Qxe2 dxe2 33. Bxc7 axb5 34. cxb5 {This position can be reached via many move orders, as we have seen. Only one game was played (Bjerre-Sindarov) and Black made a decisive mistake:} Bg4 $1 {Is Black's only defence. He needs to have the bishop on f3 on the next move.} (34... f4 $4 35. Nc3 $1 (35. Bxf4 $4 {But White also made a mistake, and after} Rf6 $18 {[%cal Gf6f4,Gf6f1] Rxf4 or Rf1+ next, and Black was winning in Bjerre-Sindarov, 2023.}) 35... f3 36. Bg3 {Black doesn't have any counterplay, and our position is winning. For example:} Bg2 (36... Re8 37. d4 Re3 38. Kd2 $18) 37. d4 f2+ 38. Bxf2 Bxc6 39. bxc6 Rxc6 40. Nxe2 $18) (34... Bg2 35. Nc3 Bf3 {is the same.}) 35. Nc3 Bf3 $1 36. Bf4 $5 {This is our best try. Now, Black has to play the only move} (36. d4 {Is not strong anymore because of} Re3 37. Ba5 {Black has a lot of moves to make a draw (Ke6/f4/Re8/Rd3)}) (36. Bg3 $5 {also deserves attention.}) 36... Ke7 $1 (36... Ke8 $4 {is losing because of} 37. d4 Rg6 38. Nxe2 Rg2 39. Nc3 Rc2 40. Bd2 $18 {compared to 36...Ke7, Black doesn't have Kd6.}) 37. Bg3 $5 {We play for the zugzwang.} (37. d4 Rg6 $1 38. Nxe2 Rg2 39. Nc3 Rc2 40. Bd2 Kd6 $11) (37. Bg5+ $5 {can be another tricky idea, for example:} Kd6 38. d4 Rg6 $1 39. Bf4+ Ke7 $1 (39... Ke6 $4 {is natural but losing!} 40. Nxe2 Rg2 41. Nc3 Rc2 42. d5+ $1 {This is the difference with 39...Ke7.} Bxd5 43. Nxd5 Kxd5 44. c7 $18 {[%cal Gb5b6,Gb6b7]}) 40. Nxe2 Rg2 41. Nc3 Rc2 $11 {What I want to say is that the position is objectively holdable for Black, but White has a lot of tries and Black should always find the best defences, which is not very pleasant for him from the practical point of view.}) 37... h6 38. d4 Re3 39. Kd2 f4 40. Bf2 $1 {e1 Bxe1} Kd6 $11 {Bf2 Re8 And it's a draw.}) 24. Qh4 $1 {only move for us.} Kh8+ 25. Kf2 Rg2+ 26. Ke3 Ne6 27. c4 $1 {[%cal Gc1b2] We prepare Bb2+. Until here, Black's moves were forced.} Bg4 (27... Kg8 $5 {is another possibility, but it gives us more choice.} 28. b5 {most challenging try.} (28. Nc3 $5 f4+ 29. Kxe4 f3 30. Kxf3 Ng5+ 31. Kf4 Rf8+ 32. Ke3 Rf3+ 33. Kd4 Ne6+ 34. Kd5 Rg5+ 35. Qxg5+ Nxg5 36. b5 {According to the engine it is a draw, but Black should be 100% sure about that!}) 28... f4+ 29. Kxe4 Rxh2 $1 30. Ke5 $3 {Fantastic move which allows us to still fight for the advantage.} Re2+ 31. Be4 Ng7+ 32. Kd5 R2xe4 33. Bb2 Bf1 $3 {Black's defensive idea.} 34. Bxg7 (34. Qg5 R4e7 35. Bxg7 Rxg7 36. Qxf4 Rf8 $11 {The engine thinks it's a draw.}) 34... Kxg7 (34... Bxc4+ 35. Kc5 Kxg7 36. Qg5+ Kf8 $1 37. d4 Bf7 $1 38. bxa6 Re2 $11 {Is another strong defense that the engine finds.}) 35. d4 $1 axb5 36. cxb5 Bxb5 37. Nc3 Bxc6+ $1 38. Kxc6 Rxd4 {Logical, but after} (38... R4e6+ $1 {The best move to make a draw:} 39. Kc5 Rf8 $1 40. Nd1 f3 41. Nf2 Rf7 $11) 39. Qg5+ Kf7 40. Qf5+ Kg7 41. Nd5 Rde4 $1 42. Qd7+ Kh8 43. Qf7 $36 {It's not guaranteed that Black will make a draw.}) 28. Qf6+ Kg8 29. Nc3 Rxh2 $1 (29... f4+ $2 {loses in beauty:} 30. Kxe4 f3 31. Nd1 $1 Rf8 (31... f2 32. Nxf2 Rf8 33. Qh4 Rfxf2 34. Kd5 $18) 32. Qh6 f2 {And now our only winning move is} 33. Ke5 $3 {We treat a mate on h7.} Bf5 (33... Rf7 34. Nxf2 Rgxf2 35. Be4 $18 {[%csl Ge5] Our king is very safe on e5, and our position is winning.}) 34. Nxf2 Nd8 $3 {[%cal Gd8f7] The idea is Nf7+, and White has another fantastic winning move:} 35. Be4 $3 Nf7+ (35... Bxe4 36. Kxe4 Rfxf2 37. d4 $18) 36. Kd4 Nxh6 37. Bxg2 $18) 30. Bd1 $1 {We are happy with the bishops exchange, so Black's play is now forced:} f4+ 31. Kxe4 Ng7+ 32. Kd3 $1 {First we provoke Bf5+} (32. Kd4 $6 {allows} Rh6 $11) 32... Bf5+ {and only now we play} 33. Kd4 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Rh2h6,Rg7f5] Where Black doesn't have the Rh6+ resource because the f5 square is not available for the knight.} Ne6+ 34. Ke5 $1 Ng7+ 35. Kd5 $1 f3 (35... Rh3 36. b5 f3 37. Bxf3 Rxf3 {transposes.}) 36. Bxf3 Rf2 37. b5 Rxf3 38. Kc5 $1 {Black's position looks lost, but he can still defend with only moves:} Rf1 $1 {[%cal Gf5d3,Gf1c1] Black's only move, with the double idea Rxc1 and Bd3.} (38... axb5 $2 39. Nxb5 Be4 40. Qh4 $1 {[%cal Gb5c7] Nxc7 is a big threat.} Rf5+ 41. Kb4 Bxc6 42. Nd4 Re4 43. Qd8+ Rf8 44. Qxc7 Rxd4 45. Qxc6 $18) 39. Nd5 Rxc1 40. bxa6 Bd3 $1 {Black saves the game in a "chess study" style:} 41. Nxc7 Rxc4+ 42. Kb6 Rb8+ $1 (42... Rf8 $2 {Without the inclusion of Rb8+ Ka7 it doesn't work:} 43. Qd6 Be4 44. Nd5 $18 {No Rf7+ idea.}) 43. Ka7 Rf8 $1 44. Qd6 Be4 $3 45. Nd5 Rf7+ 46. Kb6 Ne8 $1 {Black is just in time to save the game. White has different tries, but it's always a draw. For example:} 47. Qg3+ Kf8 48. Qa3+ Kg7 49. a7 Bxd5 $11 {a8 Rxc6+ axc6 Bxc6 Kxc6 Nf6 Black's position is a fortress. CONCLUSIONS: As we have seen, after 21...Qxg7, Black's position is not lost, but he needs to play very well and sometimes his position is holdable only after a "study-style" solution. Of course, you shouldn't remember all this variations, but I wanted to share with you to make you see how interesting are the arising positions, and so that you can have an idea of how the game could develop. Sometimes you will have a slightly different position, but you will be able to use one idea that you remember from this lesson!} *

