1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bb7 7. d3 { [%csl Rb7,Gd3,Ge4] From the positional point of view, the move d2-d3 is very good when Black has developed the bishop on b7. Very often, Black will need to lose time to maneuver his bishop back Bc8-Be6. } 7... Be7 { This move will probably transpose to the Classical Spanish 6...Be7. } 8. Nc3 ( 8. c4 $5 { Is an interesting extra option. } ) 8... O-O ( 8... d6 9. a3 O-O { transposes in Chapter 2 of Spanish for White part 1. } ) 9. a3 Nd4 $5 { This is an independent option that Black can use if he doesn't want to transpose in the Classical Spanish. } ( 9... d6 { transposes in Chapter 2 of Spanish for White part 1. } ) 10. Ba2 ( 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Ne2 c5 { It's difficult to find ideas for White. For example: } 12. Bg5 ( 12. Ng3 d5 $1 13. e5 Nd7 14. Re1 Re8 $11 { Black is just in time to equalize. } 15. c3 dxc3 16. bxc3 c4 $11 ) 12... d5 $1 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Bxd5 Bxd5 15. exd5 Qxd5 $11 { Van Foreest-Carlsen, 2021. } ) 10... Nxf3+ ( 10... d6 $6 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Ne2 c5 13. Ng3 d5 14. e5 Nd7 15. Re1 Re8 { Compared to the 10.Nxd4 variation, we have an extra move Ba2, and this is important because c5-c4 will not come with tempo: } 16. c3 Bf8 $1 ( 16... dxc3 $6 { Black shouldn't play in the same way as in the 10.Nxd4 variation, because after } 17. bxc3 c4 $2 { [%csl Ga2] Our bishop is on a2 and not on b3, so we can play } 18. d4 $18 { [%cal Ga2b1] With a decisive positional advantage. } ) 17. cxd4 cxd4 18. Bf4 $14 { Black has some problems. } ) 11. Qxf3 d6 { Black's position is solid but passive and slightly worse. We have different good directions: } 12. h3 $5 { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gh3g4] This is much more rare than 12.Qe2, and it's also my recommendation. We take control of the important g4 square against Bc8-Bg4 ideas. } ( 12. Ne2 d5 $13 ) ( 12. Qe2 { [%cal Gf2f4] White's most common continuation, with the idea to prepare f2-f4. } 12... Bc8 $1 { [%cal Gc8e6] Black reactivates his bishop. } ( 12... c6 13. f4 $14 ) ( 12... Nd7 $6 13. Nd5 $14 ) 13. Nd5 ( 13. f4 Bg4 $1 14. Qf2 Be6 $13 { Still playable, but Black is objectively fine. } ) 13... Nxd5 ( 13... c6 $6 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. f4 $14 ) 14. Bxd5 Rb8 15. a4 ( 15. Be3 Bd7 $13 ) 15... b4 16. Be3 { [%csl Rb8][%cal Ge3a7] Ba7 is a serious threat. } 16... c5 17. f4 exf4 18. Rxf4 Be6 19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. Rxf8+ Qxf8 21. Rf1 Qe8 22. Qg4 $14 { /= Black is almost fine, but we still have a very small initiative. } ) 12... Bc8 $14 { This is Black's standard idea in these positions. } ( 12... c6 { [%csl Rb7] Black prepares d5, but closes his bishop: } 13. Ne2 d5 14. Ng3 $14 { [%csl Rb7,Gf3][%cal Gg3f5] } ) ( 12... c5 13. Bg5 $14 { [%cal Gg5f6,Ge7f6,Ga2d5] We are ready for Bxf6-Bxf6-Bd5. } ( 13. Ne2 d5 $1 14. Ng3 dxe4 15. dxe4 c4 $13 ) ) 13. d4 $5 { [%csl Ra8,Gf3][%cal Gf3a8] We make use of our queen on f3. } ( 13. Nd5 { is a more solid option. } 13... Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Rb8 15. Be3 Bd7 16. b4 $14 { [%csl Gd5,Ge3,Gf3][%cal Yf2f4] White's position is more comfortable, for example: } 16... c6 17. Bb3 Qc8 18. Qg3 Be6 19. d4 $14 ) 13... exd4 { Looks critical. } ( 13... Be6 { possible move, but Black should be ready to play with the doubled pawns. } 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Rd1 Qc8 16. Bxe6 fxe6 ( 16... Qxe6 17. Bg5 c6 18. Qf5 $14 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Ye6f5,Ye4f5,Gc3e4] } ) 17. Qg3 Bd6 18. f3 $14 { We can play a slightly-better long game. } ) 14. e5 dxc3 15. Qxa8 dxe5 16. Qc6 cxb2 17. Bxb2 Bd6 18. Rfe1 $36 { Complicated position, but White has some initiative thanks to the more active pieces. } *

