1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bb7 ( { The variation of this chapter can also arise from the move order: } 6... Bc5 7. a4 Bb7 8. d3 ) 7. d3 { [%csl Rb7,Gd3,Ge4] From the positional point of view, the move d2-d3 is very good when Black has developed the bishop on b7. Very often, Black will need to lose time to maneuver his bishop back Bc8-Be6. } 7... Bc5 8. a4 { Black now has three logical continuations. } 8... d6 { [%cal Rd6d5] Black doesn't want to hurry with castling but, compared with the 8...00 variation, he loses d7-d5 ideas. } ( 8... b4 { [%csl Yb4][%cal Rb1c3,Gb4c3] Black doesn't allow us to develop a knight on c3. The obvious drawback of this move is that it might be premature. } 9. Be3 $5 { A very good positional move. Once Bxe3-fxe3 is on the board, Black's bishop on b7 will be misplaced as it cannot contest our strong bishop on b3. } 9... Bxe3 ( 9... d6 10. Bxc5 dxc5 11. a5 $16 { [%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Gc2c3] We can continue with Nbd2-Nc4-c3, and we are seriously better from the strategic point of view. } ) ( 9... Ba7 10. Bxa7 Rxa7 11. d4 $1 { Black is underdeveloped to successfully face our ideas. } 11... d6 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Qxd8+ Kxd8 15. Nd2 Ke7 16. Nc4 Nd7 17. Rad1 $16 { [%csl Gb3,Gc4,Re7][%cal Gf2f4] f4 next, and our pieces are much better placed. According to the engine, we have a +0,80 advantage. } ) 10. fxe3 { [%csl Gb3,Rb7] } 10... O-O 11. a5 $5 { [%csl Rb4][%cal Rc6a5] This move is not 100% necessary, but we don't allow Na5 ideas, and sometimes the b4 pawn might be weak in the future. } 11... d6 12. Qe1 $36 { [%cal Gb1d2,Gf3h4,Ye1h4] We are ready to create a kingside initiative. } 12... Bc8 { [%cal Gc8e6] This is a logical move because Black prepares Be6, but we can play the strong } 13. d4 $1 Qe7 ( 13... Nxe4 $4 { is not possible because of the typical } 14. Bd5 $18 { [%csl Rc6,Re4] } ) 14. h3 $5 { [%csl Rb4][%cal Ge1b4] We make another useful move, using the fact that our queen is still attacking the b4 pawn. } ( 14. Nbd2 { is also fine, but maybe Black can play } 14... Nd8 $5 ) 14... Bd7 15. Nbd2 $16 { [%csl Ra6][%cal Ge1h4,Yb3c4,Yc4d3] We can continue with Qh4, and Black's position is very difficult to play. Sometimes, if Black moves his rook from a8, we can transfer our bishop to d3, from where it will protect the e4 pawn and also keep an eye on Black's a6 pawn. } ) 9. Nc3 b4 ( 9... Na5 10. Ba2 b4 11. Ne2 { Usually transposes to 9...b4, but Black has an extra option. } 11... b3 { This is a typical idea but it doesn't work so well in this concrete position. } 12. Bxb3 ( 12. Qe1 $5 bxa2 13. Qxa5 $14 { Is another interesting direction. } ) 12... Nxb3 13. cxb3 O-O 14. Qc2 $14 { [%cal Gc1d2,Gb3b4,Ge2g3] We can continue with Ng3-Bd2-b4. Black has some compensation for the missing pawn, but not a full one. } ) 10. Ne2 O-O { might be risky, because after } ( 10... h6 { [%cal Rc1g5,Ge8g8] This is a safer move because Black wants to prevent Bg5 ideas before castling. } 11. Ng3 ( 11. a5 $5 { deserves attention. } ) 11... O-O ( 11... Na5 { Black takes the chance to play Na5 before we pushed a4-a5. } 12. Ba2 O-O { White has different interesting moves, but I like the following one: } 13. Nf5 $5 ( 13. h3 $5 ) 13... Bc8 $1 { Black is ready for Bxf5. } ( 13... d5 $2 14. Nxe5 dxe4 { Maltsevskaya-Vaishali, 2015. } 15. Bxh6 $18 ) ( 13... Rb8 $2 { This looks like a useful waiting move, but after } 14. Qd2 $18 { [%cal Gf5g7,Gf5h6] We have Nxg7 or Nxh6 ideas, and our position is immediately winning. } ) 14. N3h4 { [%csl Yf5][%cal Yh4f5] } 14... Kh7 { [%cal Gf6g8,Gg7g6] Black prepares the standard Ng8-g6 idea. } 15. c3 $14 { Not so easy to play for Black. According to the engine, } 15... b3 $1 { Is by far Black's strongest continuation, but after } 16. Bxb3 Nxb3 17. Qxb3 $14 { It's still not clear if he has full compensation for the missing pawn. } ) 12. a5 $5 { [%csl Ya6][%cal Rc6a5] We prevent Na5 ideas, and we fix Black's a6 pawn. } 12... d5 $1 { This is Black's strongest continuation