s standard continuation. } ( 12... Nd4 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 14. c3 Bb6 15. Re1 $14 { [%csl Rb7][%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3] Nf1-Ne3 next. Compared to the Italian, Black's bishop on b7 is misplaced. } ) 13. h4 $1 g4 14. Nh2 Qd7 $1 { It's better for Black to don't play h5. } ( 14... h5 15. Kh1 $40 { [%cal Gf2f3] } ) 15. Re1 $14 { [%cal Gd2f1] Black's position is very unpleasant. Let's follow the recent game Warmerdam-Tin, 2024. } ( 15. Kh1 Ng6 16. f3 $6 { is not so good now because of } 16... Nh5 $36 { That's why we go for the Kh1-f3 plan only after Black has played h5, as in the 14...h5 example. } ) 15... Kh7 16. Ndf1 Ng6 17. c3 { [%cal Gd3d4] White is ready for d4. } 17... Rae8 18. Bc2 Bb6 19. Ne3 Bc8 $2 ( 19... Bxe3 $1 { was Black's best defence, but after } 20. Rxe3 $16 { White still has a serious advantage. } ) 20. Nf5 $6 ( 20. d4 $18 { Would have been decisive. } ) 20... Ne7 $1 { Black is back in the game. } 21. d4 $2 { Second mistake. Objectively, Black's position is now absolutely fine, but it's still difficult to play, and Black lost in 5 moves: } ( 21. Ne3 $1 { White still has an advantage. } ) 21... Nxf5 22. exf5 exd4 $4 ( 22... Rg8 $13 { Was Black's only move. } ) 23. Re6 $1 Qd8 24. Rxf6 Qxf6 25. Nxg4 Qh8 26. Qd2 $18 { Black resigned in Warmerdam-Tin, 2024. } ) 11. axb5 { White's most interesting direction, in my opinion. } 11... axb5 12. Rxa8 Bxa8 ( 12... Qxa8 $6 13. Nc3 b4 ( 13... Na5 { Concrete, but dubious: } 14. Bxf7+ $1 Rxf7 15. Nxe5 Rf8 16. Ng6 Rf7 17. Nxe7+ Rxe7 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Nxb5 $16 { [%csl Rb7,Rg8] We have three pawns for the piece, and Black's king is very weak. } ) 14. Nd5 Qd8 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Qd2 $16 { [%cal Gf1a1] Ra1 next, and Black's position is just worse. } ) 13. Na3 $5 { The idea of Na3 is that in the case of b4, we can play Nc4. } ( 13. Nc3 { it's not so interesting for us: } 13... b4 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nd5 Na5 $11 { Black is fine and has a very easy play. } ) 13... Na5 $1 { Black's most precise continuation. The idea is that after 14.Ba2 b4 15.Nc4