1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 { This is Black's main system in the "Arkhangelsk world". } 7. a4 Rb8 { Now, my offer is to don't go for the mainstram 8.c3, where there is a big theory with thousands of games. We will instead go for the less explored } ( 7... Bb7 8. d3 { transposes in chapter 9. } ) 8. Nxe5 $5 ( 8. axb5 axb5 9. Nxe5 { is another option, but I prefer to take on b5 at the most convenient moment. } ) 8... Nxe5 9. d4 Bxd4 10. Qxd4 d6 { This is the main position of the variation. I want to make it immediately clear that we are not going to refute the Arkhangelsk, but we will try instead to go for less explored directions, in which Black's play is not easy. } 11. Bf4 $5 { [%csl Gf4] This is a more positional option compared to 11.f4. Now, Black can choose between 00 and c5. If you think about it, now that we have on the board a sort of "Old Philidor structure", the best square for White's bishop is exactly f4. } ( 11. f4 Nc6 { [%cal Yd4c3,Yd4d3] Leads to a very big theory, where Black needs to be precise, but he finally equalizes. White can choose now between Qc3 and Qd3. } ) 11... c5 { Black's most concrete continuation. } ( 11... O-O { This is less concrete compared to c5, and White can play a long positional game. For example: } 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rd1 $1 { [%csl Yd6][%cal Rc7c5,Gd4d6] We prevent c5. Black's position is solid, but he doesn't have a clear way to fully equalize. } 13... Bg4 { This is a bit concrete, but only for a few moves: } ( 13... Qe7 { Just a normal move, but after } 14. Nc3 h6 15. f3 $14 { White gets the desired slightly better positional game. } ) ( 13... Ng6 $14 14. Bg3 Nh5 ( 14... Be6 15. Nd2 Bxb3 ( 15... Re8 16. Bxe6 Rxe6 17. f3 $14 { [%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3] Nf1-Ne3 next. } ) 16. Nxb3 Re8 17. f3 Ra8 18. Rxa8 Qxa8 19. Qb4 $14 { [%cal Gd1a1] Our pieces are more active, and we can play against Black's slightly weak queenside pawns. } ) 15. Qe3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Be6 17. Nd2 $14 { Black is solid, but White's position is more pleasant, and the game continues. } ) 14. Bxe5 dxe5 15. Qxd8 Rbxd8 16. Rxd8 Rxd8 17. Nc3 c6 18. f3 Bd7 19. Kf2 $14 { We control the very important 'a' file, and our king is closer to the center. We can definitely play this risk-free endgame. } ) 12. Qe3 ( 12. Qd2 $5 { also deserves attention. } 12... c4 ( 12... Nxe4 $2 13. Qe1 $18 ) 13. Ba2 O-O 14. f3 Be6 15. Nc3 b4 16. Ne2 $13 { Black is objectively fine, but the position is very playable. } ) 12... c4 13. Ba2 { [%csl Ra2] Black decided to close our bishop on a2. } 13... O-O ( 13... Nh5 $5 { This computer-style move was played only once in the game Durabayli-Vidit, 2021. Black's play is objectively risky, but it's justified by strong engines. } 14. Bxe5 $14 { This is the critical continuation, and we should go for it. } ( 14. Nc3 { Was chosen by Durbayili, but after } 14... Nxf4 15. Qxf4 O-O 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rad1 Be6 18. Bb1 b4 $1 19. Ne2 Qb6 $36 { Black has already the easier position, and finally won the game. } ) 14... dxe5 15. axb5 axb5 16. b3 $1 { A human continuation would be } 16... cxb3 ( 16... Nf4 $1 { Engine's top line. } 17. bxc4 Bh3 $3 18. Nc3 Bxg2 $1 ( 18... Qg5 $6 19. Qg3 $1 { Black no longer has Ne2+, and White should have an advantage after } 19... Qh6 20. cxb5 Bxg2 21. Rfe1 O-O 22. Bc4 $14 ) 19. Rfd1 { Black can choose between Qg5, Qf6 or Qc8, and they all lead to a "0.00" position. It's a very new direction, which is still unknown by the theory. Even if the position is objectively equal, it doesn't mean that a practical game would end in a draw. For example: } 19... Qg5 { This looks as Black's most logical move. } ( 19... Qc8 { This move was played in a correspondence game. Now, I want to try } 20. Rd5 $5 Nxd5 21. exd5 Qg4 22. Qxe5+ Kd7 23. Qg3 Qxg3 24. fxg3 Bh3 25. Nxb5 { This position looks very unpleasant for Black, but the engine finds } 25... Rhe8 $1 ( 25... Ra8 $6 { Black's most natural move, but after } 26. c5 $36 { White has some initiative. } ) 26. Bb3 Re2 27. Nc3 Rg2+ 28. Kh1 Rd2 29. c5 $13 { And he thinks that this will end in a draw. } ) ( 19... Qf6 20. cxb5 O-O 21. Qg3 Qh6 $1 { Only move to equalize, and after } 22. Bc4 { we transpose in 19...Qg5. } ) 20. Qg3 Qh6 21. cxb5 O-O 22. Bc4 $13 { [%cal Ga1a6,Yh2h4,Yg1h2] We are ready for Ra6, or h4-Kh2. In case of Rbc8 (or Rfc8) we can consider the Ra6-Rc6 maneuver. Yes, it's objectively equal, but still very playable. } ) 17. Bxb3 O-O { Where Black is very solid, but after } 18. Nd2 { [%cal Yc8e6] Black still needs to equalize. His main idea should be, in my opinion, to prepare Be6. } 18... Nf4 { [%cal Gd8g5,Gc8e6] Black prepares both Qg5 and Be6. } ( 18... Re8 { Black wants to play Be6. } 19. Nf3 Be6 20. Rfd1 Qc8 $1 ( 20... Qf6 $6 21. Ra7 $16 ) 21. Ra7 $36 { Black's position is still not easy from a practical point of view. } ) ( 18... Qf6 { This is not a good way to prepare Be6. } 19. g3 { We cover the important f4 square. } 19... Be6 20. Ra6 $1 { This is why Qf6 is not a good way to prepare Be6. } 20... Rfe8 21. Nf3 $16 { [%cal Yf1d1] White is better. } ) 19. Nf3 Qf6 20. g3 Ne6 21. Rfd1 { If White can play Kg2, our position will be slightly better, but Black is in time to play } 21... Nc5 $1 22. Qxc5 Qxf3 { where White's best chance is to enter in an endgame after } 23. Rd3 Qxe4 24. Re3 Qd4 25. Qxe5 Qxe5 26. Rxe5 $14 { /= White is symbolically better because the pieces are more active, but there is not too much material left on the board, and the game should normally end in a draw. } ) 14. Rd1 Re8 ( 14... Qe7 $6 { allows } 15. Nc3 b4 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 $16 { [%csl Rc4][%cal Gd1d4] And Black has problems with the pawn on c4. } ) 15. Nc3 { Now, Black cannot play Bb7 because the b5 pawn would be hanging. That's why he should probably start with } ( 15. h3 $5 { is also possible, for example: } 15... Bb7 16. f3 Nh5 17. Bh2 f5 $1 18. Nc3 Bc6 19. Rd4 $36 { It's a new position where White has some initiative. } ) 15... b4 16. Ne2 { [%cal Gh2h3] } 16... Neg4 $14 { Black's strongest continuation. Only after this move Black can fight for a full equality, but, as we will see, the following variations are very complicated for him, and 16...Neg4 is already a novelty. } ( 16... Bb7 $6 { But now we are in time to protect our e4 pawn by playing } 17. Ng3 $16 { And our position is suddenly much better from the strategic point of view. } ) ( 16... Nh5 $2 { loses, of course, material. } 17. Bxe5 Rxe5 18. Bxc4 $18 ) ( 16... Qc7 { Was played in the game Palac-Lenic, 2010. } 17. h3 $1 { This is a much better move for White compared to 17.f3. After } ( 17. f3 { was chosen by Palac, but after } 17... Nh5 $11 { Black would have been immediately fine. } ) 17... Be6 18. Rd4 { We transpose in 16...Be6. } ) ( 16... Be6 { This is a normal-looking move, but after } 17. h3 ( 17. Bxe5 Ng4 $13 { is Black's idea. } ) 17... Qc7 18. Rd4 $14 { [%cal Ga1d1] Rad1 next, and White has a serious pressure. } ) 17. Qd4 b3 $1 { Engine's recommendation, but a very hard one for a human. } ( 17... Nxe4 { This is Black's most natural move. } 18. Ng3 $1 Ngxf2 ( 18... Nxg3 19. Bxg3 b3 20. cxb3 cxb3 21. Bb1 $16 { [%csl Rd6] We will recover the d6 pawn, and then we will be better because our bishops will be very strong in this open position. } ) ( 18... Nexf2 $4 19. Nh5 $18 ) 19. Nh5 f6 20. Bxc4+ Be6 ( 20... Kh8 21. Rf1 Qa5 $1 ( 21... Bg4 $6 22. Ng3 ( 22. Nxg7 $5 Kxg7 23. Be3 $14 { We will recover the knight and have then a better position thanks to the pair of bishops and the better structure. } ) 22... Nxg3 23. Bxg3 Ne4 24. Bf4 $14 { We not only have compensation but also an advantage thanks to our very active pieces and to the pair of bishops. } ) 22. Nxf6 $3 Nh3+ { only move for Black. } 23. gxh3 Nxf6 24. Bg3 $36 { [%csl Gc4,Gg3][%cal Yf1f6] The material is equal, but our two bishops are very strong. Rxf6 is also a big threat. } ) 21. Re1 $1 Qc8 $1 { Now, we have a lot of possible continuations, but I like the following one: } ( 21... Bxc4 $2 22. Qxc4+ Kh8 23. Qxa6 $16 { is just better for White. } ) 22. Be2 $5 Bf7 $1 { Only move for Black. } 23. Ng3 Nxg3 24. hxg3 Ne4 25. Bd3 f5 26. g4 $1 { Black needs to find now } 26... Qc5 $1 { and after } 27. Qxc5 Nxc5 28. Bf1 Rxe1 29. Rxe1 Nxa4 30. b3 Nc3 31. gxf5 $36 { [%csl Gf1,Gf4] We have a slightly better endgame thanks to our strong pair of bishops. This one should be objectively holdable for Black, but in a practical game, it could be unpleasant. } ) 18. cxb3 { And only now does the engine take on e4. } 18... Nxe4 ( 18... cxb3 $4 19. Bb1 $18 { White has a winning advantage. } ) 19. f3 g5 $1 { We are in a new territory. Here, we can try to move the bishop to every possible square. } 20. Bc1 $5 { This is my favorite move, because Black needs to find the very difficult Nef2! } ( 20. Bg3 Nxg3 21. Nxg3 Qf6 $1 { This is Black's only move to equalize. } 22. Qxf6 Nxf6 23. Rxd6 Kg7 24. Rad1 cxb3 25. Bb1 $11 { The endgame is equal, but still not a 100% draw. } ) ( 20. Bd2 Nxd2 21. Rxd2 cxb3 22. Bxb3 Rxb3 23. fxg4 Qb6 $11 { Looks fine for Black. } ) 20... Nef2 $3 ( 20... Nc5 $4 21. Ng3 Ne5 22. bxc4 $18 { White is winning. } ) ( 20... cxb3 { This is Black's most natural continuation, but after } 21. Bb1 Nc5 22. Ng3 Ne5 23. f4 $36 { White has a serious initiative. } ) 21. Rd2 Nd3 $1 { Black needs to find many only moves. } 22. fxg4 Bxg4 $1 23. Rxd3 { This is the safest continuation, and after } ( 23. Qxg4 $4 { is bad only because of } 23... Qb6+ $19 ) ( 23. bxc4 $5 Bxe2 24. h4 $13 { It's a new position that looks playable for both sides. } ) 23... cxd3 24. Nc3 ( 24. Qxg4 $2 h6 $17 ) 24... Re1+ 25. Kf2 d2 $1 ( 25... Qe7 $6 { very human move, but it does not force a draw: } 26. Bxg5 $1 Qxg5 27. Kxe1 Re8+ 28. Kf1 Qh4 $1 { only move. } 29. Qxd6 Re2 $1 { only move. } 30. Qb6 { and Black holds only after } 30... a5 $3 { don't ask me why! :) } ) 26. Bxd2 ( 26. Qxd2 $2 Qf6+ $1 27. Kxe1 Re8+ 28. Ne2 Rxe2+ 29. Qxe2 Bxe2 30. Kxe2 d5 $36 { Probably a draw, but Black is the one with the initiative because our pieces are very passive. } ) 26... Rxa1 27. Nd5 { and the game will end in a draw after, for example, } 27... Be6 28. Nf6+ Kf8 ( 28... Kh8 $5 { Black can decide to play on, but after } 29. Nd7+ f6 30. Nxb8 Rxa2 31. Nxa6 $13 { The position looks more risky for him, in my opinion. } ) 29. Nxh7+ Kg8 30. Nf6+ $11 *

